<DOCNO> XIE19980427.0002 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Exercise Shows U.S. Unable to Cope with Germ War </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 26 (Xinhua) -- A secret exercise held last
month showed that the United States is unprepared to cope with a
germ war, The New York Times reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The drill simulated a smallpox hybrid virus that was spread by
terrorists along the Mexican-American border, primarily in
California and the southwest. As the scenario unfolded, officials
playing the role of state and local officials were quickly
overwhelmed by a panicked population, thousands of whom were
falling ill and dying.
</P>
<P>
It discovered huge gaps in logistics, legal authority and
medical care.
</P>
<P>
The outcome of the exercise surprised some participants but
illustrated what others had long suspected: the United States is
still unprepared to respond to biological terror weapons, despite
huge investments of time, money and effort in recent years, the
Times said.
</P>
<P>
The findings of the exercise would support U.S. President Bill
Clinton's effort to increase the U.S. readiness to deal with a
terrorist attack.
</P>
<P>
Clinton is expected to sign two new directives this week that
provide a sweeping plan for dealing with chemical, biological or
computer-related weapons, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
In 1995, Clinton signed a Presidential Decision Directive to
underscore the need for stopping terrorists from acquiring weapons
of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
The goal of the two new Presidential Decision Directives, known
as PDD-62 and PDD-63, is to enhence the country's ability to
prevent chemical, biological or cyber-weapon attacks, and if
deterrence fails, to respond more effectively to the mayhem, the
Times said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
