<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Private Sector Urged to Lead Integration in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 26 (Xinhua) -- The Common Market for Eastern and
Southern Africa (COMESA) has urged the private sector to take
an active role in developing economies, thereby expedite economic
integration in the region.
</P>
<P>
A report, which sets out COMESA plans for the new millenium,
was released Sunday at the ongoing Zimbabwe international trade
fair, announces the formation of the Eastern and Southern African
Business Organisation (ESABO) through which the private sector in
COMESA and SADC (Southern African Development Community)
countries will network.
</P>
<P>
The report said COMESA recognized the private sector's central
position in the production and distribution of goods and services
and general creation of wealth, reported the Zimbabwe News
Agency.
</P>
<P>
''The business community is increasingly becoming an intergral
part of the economic fabric of the region. In the new millenium
the strategy will require fuller involvement of the private
sector in all areas,'' said the report.
</P>
<P>
It said that last year COMESA carried out an assessment of the
chambers of industry and commerce to identify products and
activities that could assist the member states to effectively
participate in and benefit from integration.
</P>
<P>
This resulted in a number of activities which were introduced
to support the business community to improve and be more
competitive.
</P>
<P>
The activities include enterprise specific assistance, supply
and demand surveys, buyers/sellers contact promotion meetings,
trade fairs, information networks, marketing missions and
training.
</P>
<P>
The report calls for a continuous dialogue between the COMESA
policy organs and the private sector to create an environment
conducive to business participation in regional development.
</P>
<P>
It also urged the COMESA member states to deregulate their
economies by adopting appropriate macro-economic policies and to
create a conducive investment code for favourable private sector
investment climate. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
