<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-26 16:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cypriot President Returns from Greece </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, April 26 (Xinhua) -- Cypriot President Glafcos
Clerides Sunday returned from a three-day visit to Greece, where
he held talks with Greek Premier Costas Simitis on the Cyprus
issue.
</P>
<P>
Clerides did not comment on his hour-long meeting with Simitis
upon returning at the airport. But it was was believed that the
two focused on the upcoming trip to Cyprus by United States
presidential emissary Richard Holbrooke.
</P>
<P>
Holbrooke is expected to arrive here on May 2 in a new effort
to bring the Greek Cypriot-dominated government and the Turkish
Cypriots back to the negotiating table.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash walked out of talks with
the Greek Cypriot side last summer when the European Union decided
to hold talks with Cyprus on its entry into the multi-nation body.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided since 1974 when Turkey landed its
troops on the island and took over the northern third subsequent
to a failed coup by supporters of union with Greece.
</P>
<P>
Holbrooke visited Cyprus early this month, but left
empty-handed due to Denktash's insistence that he will not
participate in talks unless his northern entity is internationally
recognized.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Cypriots declared unilaterally in 1983 the
breakaway "Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus," which is
recognized only by Ankara.
</P>
<P>
Clerides, however, appeared optimistic last Friday after
meeting with U.S. State Department Coordinator Thomas Miller in
Athens.
</P>
<P>
Clerides was quoted by Cyprus state radio as saying that Miller
would be bringing to Cyprus "a lot more than expected."
</P>
<P>
Before leaving for Greece last Friday, Clerides said there was
no sign that Turkey or the Turkish Cypriot side would respond
positively to a resumption of the intercommunal talks.
</P>
<P>
During his stay in Greece, Clerides also attended the funeral
of late Greek President Constantinos Karamanlis, who passed away
on April 23. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
