<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-26 16:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Netanyahu, Ross Hold Second Meeting on Pullback </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 26 (Xinhua) -- United States peace envoy
Dennis Ross held a second meeting here Sunday with Israeli Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu, as Israeli cabinet repeated its
refusal to accept the U.S. pullback plan.
</P>
<P>
Ross, who arrived here Saturday together with Assistant
Secretary of State Martin Indyk, was trying to win Israel's
acceptance of the U.S. proposal for a 13.1 percent pullback in the
West Bank in exchange for Palestinian security promises. No
progress has been reported over Ross' first meeting with Netanyahu
held late Saturday.
</P>
<P>
But Israel's hardline right-wing cabinet, at a weekly session
Sunday, reiterated its firmness on rejecting the U.S. proposal. It
demanded cancellation of the third redeployment and fulfillment of
obligations by the Palestinian National Authority (PNA).
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu cut short the weekly cabinet session so as to hold
another meeting of his inner cabinet to discuss the further
redeployment and his second meeting with Ross. The inner cabinet
also includes Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai, National
Infrastructure Minister Ariel Sharon, and Industry and Trade
Minister Natan Sharansky.
</P>
<P>
Speaking on the state-run TV Channel I, Netanyahu said Israel
will insist on two principles in dealing with the Palestinians:
the PNA must keep its obligations in the signed agreements and
Israel's security perimeter must be safeguarded.
</P>
<P>
David Bar-Illan, Netanyahu's media adviser, said Sunday that
the obligations that Israel urged the PNA to fulfill included
fighting terrorism, reducing police forces and stopping activities
in East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
He called on the PNA to ink agreements "that were on the verge
of signing," namely the opening of the Gaza airport and the Karni
industrial park. He said that in so doing, it would "give anybody
the sense of encouragement and progress" and would help push
forward the stalled peace process.
</P>
<P>
Before meeting with Netanyahu in the afternoon, Ross and Indyk
held an hour-long meeting with Mordechai. They discussed both the
redeployment issue and Israel's initiative on a unilateral pullout
from south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Late Sunday, Ross traveled to Gaza for a meeting with Arafat,
in a bid to break the year-old deadlock in the Israeli-Palestinian
peace process. Arafat has endorsed the U.S. plan and hoped the
U.S. to pressure Israel to accept it.
</P>
<P>
Ross's visit was mainly aimed at setting the stage for the
London talks early May, in which U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright will hold separate meetings with Netanyahu and
Arafat to bridge their gaps.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu was trying to dissuade the U.S. from publicizing its
redeployment plan, reportedly to be made known during the London
talks. He is facing stiff opposition within his right-wing
coalition to any pullback over 9 percent of the West Bank. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
