<HEADLINE> Taliban, Northern Alliance Call for End to Fighting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, April 26 (Xinhua) -- Delegates of the Taliban and
the rival Northern Alliance attending the peace talks here Sunday
appealed to their respective leadership not to launch major
military offensives against each other.
</P>
<P>
"The Steering Committee agreed that each side will appeal (to)
its leadership to agree to continue the moratorium on launching
any major offensive against each other," said James Ngobi, acting
head of the U.N. Special Mission on Afghanistan, at a press
briefing after the conclusion of the second session of the
Steering Committee.
</P>
<P>
The appeal has been made after Saturday's fighting north of the
Afghan capital of Kabul, which was reported to have left about 50
people dead.
</P>
<P>
The second session of the Steering Committee Sunday afternoon
lasted for three hours. The talks was supervised by Assistant
Secretary General of the Organization of Islamic Conference Saleh
Bakar and Ngobi.
</P>
<P>
Ngobi said the Steering Committee held its second session
Sunday afternoon and continued its consideration of procedural
issues.
</P>
<P>
The Committee will continue to consider procedural issues at
its next session scheduled for Monday morning, he added.
</P>
<P>
Asked if the Steering Committee decided any provisional agenda
of the talks, Ngobi said, "that will be discussed. It continues to
be discussed."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Northern Alliance has described as "highly
successful" the two rounds of talks of the Steering Committee and
expected positive results.
</P>
<P>
The two warring Afghan factions began their peace talks here
Sunday morning. It is the first face-to-face meeting between the
two sides in more than a year.
</P>
<P>
The peace talks are expected to last three to five days as
agreed by the two sides in the session Sunday morning. 
</P>
</TEXT>
