<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-26 17:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> United Front Ready to Negotiate with Taliban: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 26 (Xinhua) -- Leader of the Afghan National
Islamic Movement Abdulrashid Dostum said here on Sunday that the
National Islamic United Front of Afghanistan is ready to negotiate
with the Taliban group.
</P>
<P>
During a meeting with Iran's Special Envoy for Afghan Affairs
Alaeddin Boroujerdi, Dostum said the United Front has the
responsibility to prevent massacre of innocent civilians and bring
peace to the country, Iran's official news agency IRNA reported.
</P>
<P>
The National Islamic United Front of Afghanistan is fighting
the Taliban Islamic group which took over the capital of Kabul in
1996 and ousted the Afghan government of President Burhanuddin
Rabbani.
</P>
<P>
"If our enemies are not serious about peace and opt to fight
us, we will defend our people with all might," Dostum said,
hailing the United Front as a group of unity and playing the
greatest role in Afghan developments.
</P>
<P>
Reports reaching here said the Taliban and its northern-based
alliance ended their first day of negotiations, which are
co-sponsored by United Nations and the Organization of the Islamic
Conference (OIC) on Sunday in Pakistan and expected to last for
three to five days.
</P>
<P>
The two sides are negotiating a cease-fire, prisoner exchange
and a committee of Islamic scholars whose decisions would be
binding on the warriors.
</P>
<P>
Dostum called on Iran, as current OIC chairman, to use all
means at its disposal to help resolve the Afghan crisis.
</P>
<P>
Boroujerdi said that peace would be made in Afghanistan only
with serious determination of all the Afghan factions.
</P>
<P>
Iran considers negotiations of the factions as the most
suitable way of resolving the crisis in the war-devastated
country, the Iranian official said.
</P>
<P>
Boroujerdi termed the change of Taliban's stance as a "positive
step," which he said, if sincere, can help end the Afghan crisis.
</P>
<P>
Dostum arrived here on Saturday for a four-day visit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
