<DOCNO> XIE19980427.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-26 17:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Peres: A Palestinian State Is Possible Solution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 26 (Xinhua) -- The possible solution to the
stalled Middle East peace process is the establishment of an
independent Palestinian state, former Israeli Prime Minister
Shimon Peres said in Gaza on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
After talks with Palestinian National Authority (PNA) President
Yasser Arafat, Peres told a joint press conference that the peace
process has been stalled for a long time, and the possible solution to
it is the establishment of an independent Palestinian state.
</P>
<P>
He did not elaborate on the idea, but said that it is in the
interest of all that the Palestinian economy is strong.
</P>
<P>
Being a vehement advocate of the peace process, Peres supports
the idea of pushing the process forward through economic
cooperations between the parties concerned.
</P>
<P>
He set up a peace fund last year to help open up economic
projects in the PNA territories to help the Palestinians build
their economy.
</P>
<P>
During Sunday's talks, Perez and Arafat discussed the latest
developments in the peace process and ways of advancing it, an
informed PNA official said.
</P>
<P>
Arafat told reporters that the meeting has been important and
positive. He is scheduled to meet U.S. peace envoy Dennis Ross in
Gaza Sunday evening to discuss issues concerning the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Ross returned to region Saturday evening to try to help bring
the process back on track. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
