<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Rejects Britain's Nuclear Accusation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 26 (Xinhua) -- Iran on Sunday turned down an
accusation by British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook that it has a
program to attain nuclear technology, terming it as "unfounded."
</P>
<P>
According to the official news agency IRNA, Foreign Ministry
spokesman Mahmoud Mohammadi said Cook's claim aimed to divert the
British public opinion from the controversy surrounding the
shipment of Georgian nuclear wastes to Scotland for reprocessing.
</P>
<P>
He expressed concern over the indifference of the international
community towards the growing arm activities of Israel, saying
that Tel Aviv, through support of the U.S. and some other western
countries, has transformed the occupied territories into a depot
of new arms and ammunition which threatens the stability and
security in the region and the world.
</P>
<P>
He accused the U.S., Israel and their like of engaging in a
misinformation campaign against Iran, which he said based on its
foreign policy and attention on international regulations.
</P>
<P>
Iran has been calling for a Middle East free of weapons of mass
destruction and increased pressure on Israel for it to destroy
nuclear warheads and weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
The international community should also pressure Israel's
western supporters to end their support for non-stop growth of its
stockpile of nuclear armaments, he said.
</P>
<P>
Referring to relations between the European Union (EU) and
Iran, Mohammadi said that Tehran welcomed the desire expressed by
the EU ministers in their March 30 meeting to start dialog with
Iran.
</P>
<P>
There currently exists talks between Iran and the EU at
director general level, to define the framework of comprehensive
negotiations, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
