<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-26 17:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FM: Iran Ready to Help Solve Afghan Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 26 (Xinhua) -- Iranian Foreign Minister Kamal
Kharrazi reiterated Sunday that Iran, as chairman of the
Organization of the Islamic Conference (OIC), is ready to help
solve the Afghan crisis and bring peace and tranquillity to the
country.
</P>
<P>
In a meeting with Abdulrashid Dostum, vice president and leader
of the National Islamic Movement of Afghanistan, Kharrazi stressed
that unity among all factions would guarantee peace and stability
in Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
Dostum thanked Tehran for its peace efforts, stressing that the
National Islamic United Front (NIUF) headed by Afghan President
Burhanuddin Rabbani was determined to work for peace in the
war-torn country.
</P>
<P>
Rabbani and his government were driven out of capital Kabul in
the protracted civil war in September 1996 by Taliban militants,
who have since seized power and consolidated their rule over most
of Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
Dostum blamed the "oppressive policies" of Taliban for the
nation's many pains and sufferings, urging it to be sincere in the
forthcoming negotiations for peace.
</P>
<P>
Dostum, who arrived here Saturday for a four-day official
visit, met Iran's special envoy for Afghan affairs Alaeddin
Boroujerdi on Sunday and indicated the NIUF's readiness to
negotiate with Taliban.
</P>
<P>
Following the intervention by the U.S. ambassador to the United
Nations Bill Richardson, the NIUF and Taliban started first round
of peace talks in Islamabad, Pakistan on Sunday in an effort to
put an end to the country's civil war. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
