<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-26 18:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arab League Chief Visits Algeria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALGIERS, April 26 (Xinhua) -- Arab League (AL) Secretary
General Ahmed Esmat Abdel-Meguid arrived here on Sunday for a
three-day visit.
</P>
<P>
Upon arrival, the AL chief told reporters that he would discuss
issues of concern to the Arab world, including combating
terrorism, with President Liamine Zeroual and Algerian officials.
</P>
<P>
He said the visit came after the Arab countries signed on
Tuesday an agreement on fighting terrorism, which he described as
historic.
</P>
<P>
The agreement, the first of its kind in the Arab world,
"defines the framework of Arab actions against terrorism", he said.
</P>
<P>
"Arab states are looking forward to further cooperation and
coordination in combating terrorism, and we assert and support
every action that leads to stability and peace for all Arab
people," he added.
</P>
<P>
Algeria, an Arab country in north Africa, has been heavily hit
by Islamic insurgence since 1992 when the military-backed
government canceled a parliament election in which the Islamic
Salvation Front was poised to win.
</P>
<P>
More than 60,000 people, mostly innocent civilians, have been
killed in the bloody fighting waged by Islamic militants.
</P>
<P>
Replying to a question about the prospect of an Arab summit,
Abdel-Meguid said "there is no unanimity at present regarding the
convocation of a mini or full-fledged Arab summit, but
consultations are ongoing at top level."
</P>
<P>
Those consultations, either bilateral or multilateral, are
dealing with the Arab causes, the Middle East peace process in
particular, the Arab League chief said.
</P>
<P>
Some Arab countries have proposed to hold a summit to discuss
various issues in the Arab world and ways and means of advancing
the peace talks between Arab countries and Israel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
