<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa Sees Normal Ties with Nigeria: Envoy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 26 (Xinhua) -- South African High Commissioner to
Nigeria Sipho Nene has described the state of relations between
the two countries as "normal and cordial", saying "they are just as
normal as they are with most countries."
</P>
<P>
Although there has been no official bilateral agreements and
exchanges, "the two countries are on a very normal and cordial
relations," the envoy said, quoted by the News Agency of Nigeria
on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
According to Nene, the nature of Nigeria's transition to civil
rule program has had an impact on both countries in the area of
bilateral cooperation.
</P>
<P>
It has been repeatedly reported that the two countries have
been vying for the leadership of Africa, with an aim to represent
the continent to seat among permanent members in a planned
expanded United Nations Security Council.
</P>
<P>
The bilateral relations became cold following Nigeria's
refusal of calls from the international community, including
South Africa, not to execute nine minority activists in 1995.
</P>
<P>
South Africa was one of the countries advocating sanctions
against Nigeria, including the two-year suspension of Nigeria
from the Commonwealth.
</P>
<P>
It also joined the majority of Commonwealth member states to
oppose the idea of expelling Nigeria from the 53-country
organization at a meeting last year, which decided final action
would be taken at the end of Nigeria's political transition.
</P>
<P>
Nene noted that there are a lot of possibilities for
cooperation in all spheres of the economy in both countries,
saying that "it is question of time for cooperation between both
countries to be fully exploited."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
