<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Business Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 26 (Xinhua) -- The following are business briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egyptian Trade and Supply Minister Ahmed Gowaili said
that Egypt and Kuwait will sign an agreement on free trade zone
soon.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, he added, commodities from one to the
other will enjoy a 50 percent cut in tariff, and the remaining 50
percent will be reduced gradually in the upcoming four years.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- United Arab Emirates Petroleum Minister Obeid Bin
Saif Al Nasir said Saturday that the Organization of Petroleum
Exporting Countries (OPEC) would take up the issue of further
cutting its output to bolster world oil prices at its coming June
meeting.
</P>
<P>
The incumbent OPEC chairman said that should oil prices remain
at or below the present, voices demanding production cuts would
become louder.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the present oil prices fall far short of
the satisfactory 20 dollars per barrel.
</P>
<P>
RIYADH -- The United Saudi Bank gained 147 million rials (about
39.2 million dollars) in net profit during the first quarter of
this year, an increase of 56 million rials (about 14.9 million
dollars) against the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
In a statement released Saturday, the bank attributed the
increase to more operation revenues, spending cuts, efforts to
retrieve failing debts and credit portfolio improvement after the
emerger of the United Saudi Commercial Bank and the Saudi Cairo
Bank.
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- Lebanese Minister of Rural and Municipal Affairs
Hagob Demirjian announced Friday that the World Bank has decided
to offer 60 million dollars in grant to Lebanon for its
infrastructure projects.
</P>
<P>
He said that his ministry would allocate another 30 million
dollars for implementing the infrastructure projects in various
parts of Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank has earlier provided Lebanon with 721.3 million
dollars in grants and loans to finance an 18-billion-dollar plan
for its overall reconstruction and rehabilitation.
</P>
<P>
SANAA -- Yemeni government has decided to take practical
measures to revoke the subsidies for wheat and flour by the year
2001, as part of economic reforms agreed upon with the
International Monetary Fund and the World Bank.
</P>
<P>
According to Yemeni Deputy Minister of Supply and Trade Ali Al
Siaghi, the program will be implemented on a year-by-year basis,
and will not largely affect local prices. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
