<DOCNO> XIE19980427.0027 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kohl Suffers Major Setback in Eastern German State Vote </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, April 26 (Xinhua) -- With only five months away from
national elections in September, German Chancellor Helmut Kohl saw
one of his most severe setbacks to date on Sunday when his
conservative party lost heavily in a crucial local legislature
vote in the eastern German state of Saxony-Anhalt.
</P>
<P>
In Saxony-Anhalt's statehouse race, which is viewed as a key
test of Kohl's chances to win re-election in the September 27
national vote, the chancellor's Christian Democratic Union (CDU)
scored only about 23 percent of the vote, a loss of more than 10
percentage points from its 1994 result of 34.4 percent,
preliminary computer projections showed.
</P>
<P>
Riding a surge in support nationwide, the main opposition party
in Bonn, the Social Democratic Party (SPD), increased their score
to over 37 percent from 34 percent in 1994, replacing the CDU as
the largest party in the eastern German state.
</P>
<P>
Analysts attributed the slumping popularity of the CDU mainly
to the fact that many former supporters of Kohl, who has won wide
public endorsement after leading the German reunification in 1990,
have turned against him because of his poor record to keep his
promises to revitalize the eastern German economy.
</P>
<P>
Dubbed "Germany's poorhouse", Saxony-Anhalt, which once proudly
regarded itself as a stronghold of heavy industry, now has
Germany's highest jobless rate, about 24 percent, the lowest rate
of economic growth.
</P>
<P>
With their support ratings runing about 10 percentage points
ahead of Kohl's party in Germany recently, the Social Democrats
saw the Saxony-Anhalt vote as another sign for their eventual
victory in the national elections after 16 years in opposition.
</P>
<P>
As a major alarm for the mainstream parties, the
right-extremist party German People's Union DVU managed to
capitalize on the big losses of the CDU by scoring over 10 percent
on Sunday, becoming the first radical right party to enter a state
assembly in eastern Germany since 1990.
</P>
<P>
The DVU has been put under surveillance by German
constitutional authorities because of its anti-foreigner
sentiments and appeal to neo-Nazis.
</P>
<P>
The Saxony-Anhalt election also saw the support for the
ecologist Greens party dropping from 5.1 percent in 1994 to around
three percent, short of the five percent needed to win
parliamentary seats under the German election law.
</P>
<P>
The popularity of the Greens has taken a nosedive in recent
months after it floated the unpopular idea of tripling the
country's gasoline prices in order to cover social security
deficits.
</P>
<P>
If such a trend continued, it would be a major setback for the
SPD which might have to count on an alliance with the Greens in
order to come to power in Bonn in September.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Free Democratic Party (FDP), the junior partner
in Kohl's current ruling coalition in Bonn, also failed to make
the grade to enter the statehouse of Saxony-Anhalt, though it did
improve its performance a little bit to over four percent from 3.6
percent in 1994.
</P>
<P>
The Party of Democratic Socialism (PDS) managed to keep its
position as the third largest political power in Saxony-Anhalt by
maintaining its support at about 20 percent. Hoping to ride
widespread resentment among eastern German voters, the former
communists has set a target to clear the five-percent threshold
for the first time in the national elections. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
