<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-26 20:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Denies Japan's Mediating Iran-U.S. Disputes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 26 (Xinhua) -- Iran's Deputy Foreign Minister for
Asian and Pacific affairs Mohsen Aminzadeh on Sunday denied as
rumors that Japan was mediating between Iran and the United States.
</P>
<P>
According to the official news agency IRNA, Aminzadeh said the
Japan's Deputy Foreign Minister Massahico Komura, who visited Iran
earlier this week, had simply voiced his government's pleasure
with the improving atmosphere between Tehran and Washington.
</P>
<P>
He said Iranian authorities had reminded the Japanese official
that the U.S. administration is sticking to its hostile policies
towards Iran in many aspects.
</P>
<P>
Komura arrived here Wednesday on a four-day official visit, and
delivered a written message from Japanese Prime Minister Riyutaro
Kashimoto to Iranian President Mohammadi Khatami.
</P>
<P>
Khatami met with Komura on Saturday. During the talks, Khatami
said the American people should persuade their politicians to
change their policies towards Iran; Komura, for his part, hoped
that obstacles would be removed for re-establishment of
Tehran-Washington ties.
</P>
<P>
Since Khatami called for cultural exchanges between the Iranian
and American nations in January, there have been many rumors about
direct and indirect contacts between the two sides. Iranian
officials repeatedly stated that Tehran would not resume relations
with Washington unless its hostile policies are changed.
</P>
<P>
Aminzadeh also said Komura's visit to Tehran was a big stride
for further developing relations between Iran and Japan, adding
that the Japanese had indicated their interest in more regular
exchange of official visits.
</P>
<P>
Komura was the highest-ranking Japanese official that visited
Iran since Khatami became president last August. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
