<HEADLINE> Columbia's Air Purifier Resumes Work </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 26 (Xinhua) -- The air purifying system
aboard the space shuttle Columbia resumed operation Sunday and the
crew members began focusing on their research mission again.
</P>
<P>
A leaky valve forced the shuttle's carbon dioxide removal
system to shut down late Friday which threatens to cut short the
two-week research mission focused on brain and nervous system in
weightless space.
</P>
<P>
"With some great work and support from the ground, we were able
to repair that system, and we're going to go on to a full mission
duration," shuttle Commander Richard Seaffoss said today.
</P>
<P>
There are no obstacles currently standing in the way of
Columbia completing a full mission, and NASA plans to keep the
crew in orbit at least another week and possibly until May 4, if
supplies hold out. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
