<DOCNO> XIE19980427.0031 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zanzibar President Stresses Need to Develop </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, April 26 (Xinhua) -- Zanzibar President Salmin
Amour has stressed the necessity to develop tourism in the efforts
of the isles' to diversify its economy.
</P>
<P>
Opening the five-star Breeze Beach Club on Saturday at Dongwe
in Unguja South District, Amour said the government strived to
make tourism the principal foreign exchange earner to replace
clove exports, which have shown ineptness in the isles' economic
recovery efforts in recent years.
</P>
<P>
According to a report reaching here Sunday, the president
observed that the decline of clove prices in the world market has
affected the isles' economy and stalled development projects.
</P>
<P>
Planting of cloves has been a pillar in the economy of the
twin islands of Unguja and Pemba for over 100 years. But Amour
said that the changing economic scenes have made it necessary for
the isles to choose an alternative means of development.
</P>
<P>
He further noted that tourism played a pivotal role in
securing more employment opportunities for people and in
fostering international cooperation through increased foreign
investments.
</P>
<P>
He called on Zanzibar residents to give full support to
foreign investors in developing the tourism industry in Zanzibar
so as to ease the isles' economic hardships.
</P>
<P>
The president, however, cautioned that such interactions
should not be given room to pollute Zanzibar's norms and cultural
values, which should be maintained and defended.
</P>
<P>
More than 95 percent of the population of Zanzibar, off the
east coast of the mainland of Tanzania, are Moslems. Of late,
the public have called on tour operators to keep the clean image
of Zanzibar, as some foreign visitors have come to Zanzibar
seeking not only sand and sunshine but also sex.
</P>
<P>
The opening of the beach hotel was part of celebrations to
mark the 34th anniversary of the union between then Tanganyika
and Zanzibar which reached its climax Sunday.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
