<HEADLINE> Greece: Intervention on Kosovo Should Respect Int'l Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Greece said Monday that
intervention on the crisis in the Yugoslav province of Kosovo
should always be within the framework of international law and
aimed at reducing tension there.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a meeting on the European defense and security
structure in the northern Greek city of Thessaloniki Monday, Greek
Defense Minister Akis Tsohatzopoulos described the present
situation in Kosovo as "a hand grenade ready to explode," the
semi-official Athens News Agency (ANA) reported.
</P>
<P>
There must be some kind of intervention to pressure both the
ethnic Albanians and Serbia into resuming the immediate and
unconditional dialogue, he said, adding that such intervention
should always be within the framework of international law and the
implementation of international conventions.
</P>
<P>
He added that any party which mediated or wished to mediate
would be offering its good services when they followed this policy
of reducing tension.
</P>
<P>
In Kosovo, the ethnic Albanians, who make up 90 percent of the
province's 2 million population, are demanding their independence
from Serbia.
</P>
<P>
Recently, Serbians rejected in a referendum a Western role in
Kosovo by a resounding 95 percent. 
</P>
