<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Visiting French President Jacques
Chirac expressed support for Japan's new economic policy to
stimulate the sluggish economy.
</P>
<P>
Chirac made the comment during a one-hour meeting Monday with
Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto, Japanese Foreign
Ministry officials said.
</P>
<P>
After listening to Hashimoto's explanation on the government's
latest stimulus package, Chirac said he is not worried about
Japan's economic policies, adding that he believes Japan's economy
will be fully revitalized.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders also agreed on the need for cooperation in the
May 15-17 Birmingham summit of eight major powers dealing with the
current economic and currency crisis in Asia, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
In a separate meeting, French Foreign Minister Hubert Vedrine
and his Japanese counterpart Keizo Obuchi agreed to introduce a
"working-holiday" system between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
France will be Japan's first European partner to launch such a
system in which the youths from each country can experience life
in the other's country by spending their holidays there and
supporting themselves through temporary jobs.
</P>
<P>
Chirac is now on a five-day visit to Japan to mark the start of
the Year-of-France festival. 
</P>
