<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Campaign for Easier Abortion Launched in UK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 27 (Xinhua) -- A campaign to make abortion easier
to obtain in Britain was launched Monday by an alliance of
pro-choice and family planning groups, according to media reports
Monday.
</P>
<P>
The campaign, named the Voice for Choice, was launched on the
30th anniversary of the introduction of the 1967 Abortion Act, the
first legislation on abortion all over the world.
</P>
<P>
It was supported by politicians and Peers from all parties and
came in response to evidence that abortion provision has fallen
behind public expectations.
</P>
<P>
The move called for changes to the 1967 law, under which
abortion can be carried out on request for women in the first
three months of pregnancy.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, abortion up to 24 weeks of pregnancy is only allowed
if two doctors agree that the mother would suffer mentally or
physically if her pregnancy went ahead.
</P>
<P>
"This is the first time for years that there has been so much
weight behind our campaign," said Jane Roe, co-ordinator of the
campaign.
</P>
<P>
"We are very optimistic about the chances of success," and "we
have got a lot of support among members of parliament and we feel
that all of the current cabinet is personally behind women's right
to choose," she added.
</P>
<P>
Baroness Gould of Potternewton, who chairs the campaign to mend
the law, said that "many women still have problems finding prompt,
sympathetic help. Access to NHS (National Health Service) abortion
varies widely around the country."
</P>
<P>
"It (the law) subjects women to undue stress and confusion at
what is already a very difficult and distressing period of their
lives. It is time for a change," she said.
</P>
<P>
The campaign demands that medical approval for terminations up
to 14 weeks of pregnancy should not be required at all and only
one doctor should have to give consent for abortions between 15
and 24 weeks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
