<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kiriyenko to Trim Russian Government </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Russian Prime Minister Sergei
Kiriyenko will cut the administrative staff as the first step to
streamline the bloated government, a senior Russian official said
on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Alexander Kotenkov, the Russian president's representative in
the State Duma (Russia's lower house of parliament), said at a
press conference that the presidential administration will be cut
by 300 people.
</P>
<P>
He said the Russian Security Council has already laid off 100
employees.
</P>
<P>
Ministries and government agencies performing functions that
overlap will be merged, Kotenkov said, indicating that more people
could be fired when mergers start.
</P>
<P>
Kotenkov implied that Kiriyenko would not name many lawmakers
into ministerial posts, whereas Duma Speaker Gennady Seleznyov
hoped that a coalition government could be formed.
</P>
<P>
"Although there are many able people in the lower house of
parliament, just a dozen are fit for ministerial posts," Kotenkov
said.
</P>
<P>
The 35-year-old Kiriyenko, who became the Russian prime
minister last Friday, will attempt to revive the stagnant Russian
economy; but Kotenkov said that a political and economic crisis
could strike the country in the fall.
</P>
<P>
Kotenkov blamed the political difficulty on the Duma's statement
that it would bring a non-confidence vote against the government in
September if the economy goes bust.
</P>
<P>
"If the economy is driven into a blind alley and wage and
pension arrears grow, the government is doomed," said Seleznyov.
</P>
<P>
The new government believes it can control the political crisis
but might not be able to curb the economic turmoil, said the
presidential representative. 
</P>
</TEXT>
