<HEADLINE> SIMEX to Trade Malaysia, Thailand Stock Index </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, April 27 (Xinhua) -- The Singapore International
Monetary Exchange (SIMEX) announced here Monday that it has
obtained a license from Dow Jones to create and trade futures and
options contracts based on the Dow Jones Malaysia and Thailand
Stock Indexes.
</P>
<P>
The contracts are expected to be listed on SIMEX in November
1998, SIMEX said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
It said the Dow Jones Malaysia Stock Index is a market
capitalization weighted index of 116 Malaysian stocks which covers
approximately 80 percent of the total market capitalization of the
Kuala Lumpur Stock Exchange (KLSE) of Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones Thailand Stock Index is again a market
capitalization weighted index of 71 stocks listed on the Stock
Exchange of Thailand (SET) and represents 80 percent of that
market's total capitalization.
</P>
<P>
According to the statement, the licensing agreement gives SIMEX
exclusive rights to use both the Dow Jones Malaysia and Thailand
Stock Indexes as the basis for futures and options trading during
the market hours of the two stock markets.
</P>
<P>
SIMEX President Ang Swee Tian said, "The agreement with Dow
Jones is a natural progression in our continuing effort to expand
our core group of contracts to cover more Asian markets."
</P>
<P>
"We are confident that our new contracts, to be based on the
well-established Dow Jones indexes, will prove popular with
international fund managers and investors as useful hedging and
trading instruments," he said.
</P>
<P>
SIMEX is a global futures and options exchange, which offers a
wide range of international futures and options contracts on
interest rates, currencies, stock indexes and energy products.
</P>
<P>
For stock indexes, SIMEX currently trades futures and options
contracts relating to the Japan and Taiwan stock markets. 
</P>
</TEXT>
