<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Market Value of KSE Stocks Drops 18.8 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, April 27 (Xinhua) -- The Kuwait Stock Exchange
(KSE) shares lost 1.64 billion Kuwait Dinars (5.412 billion
U.S. dollars) in market value, or 18.8 percent from the start of
this year till the latest trading week ending last Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Quoting financial reports, the Kuwait News Agency said Monday
that the plunge left the market value of KSE shares of a total of
75 listed Kuwaiti and non-Kuwaiti companies at 7.4 billion dinars
(24.42 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
Compared with the end of 1997, KSE index retreated 570.5
points, or 21.5 percent, to stand at 2,082.3 points.
</P>
<P>
Trading at KSE was mixed during the week ending last
Wednesday. The indices of volume, value and number of transactions
increased while the general index registered the second largest
decline since the reopening of KSE on September 18, 1992 after the
Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
Since last November, deals in KSE have been poor due to the
high value of shares registered in the first half of 1997. KSE
financial experts attributed this to the halt of credit operations
and margin, as well as the lack of investment tools and the
establishment of new investment funds, which forced dealers to
withdraw large sums of cash. 
</P>
</TEXT>
