<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Private Firms Might Be Granted Export Rights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, April 27 (Xinhua) -- A government official disclosed
here today that China is considering empowering the country's
private companies with the right to export goods on their own.
</P>
<P>
Under the current rules, private firms have to process export
business through state-owned firms, he said.
</P>
<P>
Liu Xiangdong, Assistant Minister of Foreign Trade and Economic
Cooperation, made the remarks here today. Liu is attending the
83rd Guangzhou Export Commodity Trade Fair.
</P>
<P>
Liu said that the rights will be first given to private
businesses in manufacturing sectors, since "the issue in the
circulation sector is more complicated".
</P>
<P>
For decades, only state-owned exporters had been granted the
right to be engaged in exporting and importing.
</P>
<P>
Since 1992, only some state-owned companies and scientific
research bodies have obtained the right to export their own
products.
</P>
<P>
However, all the firms, including private ones, in the
country's five special economic zones -- Shenzhen, Xiamen,
Shantou, Zhuhai and Hainan -- have automatically obtained the
power to export their goods regardless of their ownership status.
</P>
<P>
The official said private businesses are quite active, and it
will be beneficial to the country's foreign economic and trade
sector to allow them to do foreign trade.
</P>
<P>
The reform asks for improving the work of the supervision and
control departments, including Customs offices, banks, commodity
inspection and taxation bureaus, Liu said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
