<DOCNO> XIE19980427.0052 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Former Vietnamese Communist Party Chief Linh Dead at 82 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Nguyen Van Linh, former general
secretary of the Vietnamese Communist Party, died on Monday at the
age of 82 in southern Ho Chi Minh City, a communique said.
</P>
<P>
The communique was issued by the central committee of the
Communist Party of Vietnam (CPV), the president of Vietnam, the
National Assembly of Vietnam, the Vietnamese government, the
Vietnam Fatherland Front and the military central committee of the
CPV.
</P>
<P>
The communique said Linh "had made a great contribution to the
revolutionary cause of the CPV and the nation in his 70-year
revolutionary career," and that "his death was a great loss to the
CPV, the country and the people."
</P>
<P>
A state funeral will be held on April 29. Vietnam's national
flag will fly at half mast on April 28 and 29, and entertainment
has been forbidden, according to the CPV.
</P>
<P>
Nguyen Van Linh was born on July 1, 1915, in Hanoi. He fought
against French colonial rule in 1929, and became a member of the
Indochina Communist Party in 1936.
</P>
<P>
Nguyen Van Linh led the Vietnam people in southern Vietnam
against the United States armed forces during the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
He was elected as the general secretary of the Central
Committee of the CPV in 1986 at the sixth National Congress of the
CPV, and served as the senior party advisor at the Seventh
National Congress of the CPV.
</P>
<P>
During his term as general secretary of the central committee
of the CPV, the party was undertaking an across-the-board reform.
</P>
<P>
Linh also made significant contributions to the normalization
of Sino-Vietnamese relations and the development of bilateral
good-neighborly friendship and cooperation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
