<HEADLINE> Chinese PLA Chief of General Staff Meets Indian Defense </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Fu Quanyou, chief of general
staff of China's People's Liberation Army (PLA), Monday exchanged
views with Indian Defense Minister George Fernandes and chiefs of
the three services of Indian Armed Forces on closer ties between
the two countries and armed forces.
</P>
<P>
The atmosphere at the meeting was frank and friendly, sources
close to the meeting said.
</P>
<P>
General Fu arrived here Sunday night on a five-day official
visit to India.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, the two sides pointed out that China and
India, two ancient nations in Asia, have a traditional friendship
which has lasted for more than two thousand years.
</P>
<P>
They noted that China and India initiated the world-famous five
principles of peaceful coexistence, namely mutual respect for
territorial integrity and sovereignty, mutual non-aggression,
non-interference in each other's affairs, equality and mutual
benefit and peaceful coexistence. And they both have the desire to
maintain and develop good-neighborly relations.
</P>
<P>
Regarding the differences left over by history between the two
countries, Fu said all difficulties could be overcome gradually
through peaceful and friendly talks and negotiations as long as
the two countries want to establish good-neighborly ties.
</P>
<P>
Fu also said exchange of visits between the two countries could
enhance mutual understanding and trust.
</P>
<P>
To maintain friendly ties between China and India is not only
in the interest of the two countries, but also conducive to
regional and world peace, he said.
</P>
<P>
Fernandes and India's three services chiefs said India attaches
great importance to General Fu's visit, the first to India by the
chief of the PLA General Staff. They expressed their desire to
promote the friendship and cooperation between the two countries
and armed forces through visits and dialogue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
