<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canadians Support Ties with Cuba: Poll </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Nearly two thirds of Canadians
support the government strategy of engaging Cuba, according to a
new poll published Monday.
</P>
<P>
Sixty-five percent of those surveyed said the Canadian
government should assist Canadian companies in their fight against
the U.S. interventionism called for in the anti-Cuba Helms-Burton
law.
</P>
<P>
The poll was conducted for the Ottawa Citizen newspaper and the
Canadian National Committee of the International Institute of
Strategic Studies on April 15-18, days before Prime Minister Jean
Chretien started his landmark visit to Cuba Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Chretien's three-day visit is the first to the Caribbean island
nation by a Canadian prime minister since Pierre Trudeau made the
trip there 22 years ago at the height of the Cold War.
</P>
<P>
The poll also found that 17 percent of those surveyed said
Canada should come up with its own version of Helms-Burton
legislation, 12 percent said the U.S. law should be ignored and 5
percent said it should be obeyed.
</P>
<P>
And far more Canadians (42 percent) believe it is Ottawa's
opposition to the U.S. dictating trade rules on Cuba than an
interest in advancing Canadian economic interests (15 percent)
that motivates the government's commitment to Cuba, according to
the poll.
</P>
<P>
The poll of 500 Canadians is considered accurate to within 4.5
percent percentage points 19 times out of 20. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
