<HEADLINE> Chinese NPC Vice-Chairman Meets US Visitors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 27 (Xinhua) -- More exchanges between youth
organizations in China and the United States will be of
significance for the development of future bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
Jiang Zhenghua, vice-chairman of China's National People's
Congress (NPC) Standing Committee, said this in a meeting today
with a delegation from the American Council of Young Political
Leaders. He expressed the hope that American political figures of
the younger generation will make positive efforts to foster
bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
Jiang said that as both China and the U.S. are large countries,
the growth of their relationship will benefit both sides and
contribute to world peace and development.
</P>
<P>
A. Gifford Miller, a member of the delegation and a member of the
Council of the City of New York, told Jiang that US-China
ties are a very important bilateral relationship in the
world.
</P>
<P>
He said that the U.S. hopes to develop a "more cooperative and
stronger relationship" with China.
</P>
<P>
The American Council of Young Political Leaders, established in
1966, is a semi-official organization composed of both Republican
and Democratic party members. It established links with the
All-China Youth Federation in 1979.
</P>
<P>
This is the 16th visit to China by a delegation from the
American Council of Young Political Leaders.
</P>
<P>
Miller told Xinhua after the meeting that exchanges between
youth organizations in the two countries are important for the
enhancement of mutual understanding and mutual trust between the
peoples of the two countries.
</P>
<P>
He added that those exchanges can be a part of efforts to move
forward bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
Miller, who is 28 years old and has served as a member of the
Council of the City of New York for more than two years, said that
presidential visits between the two countries can provide good
opportunities for the growth of bilateral ties, because the
leaders can see for themselves the culture, history and values of
each other's country and thus promote mutual understanding.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the hope that President Bill Clinton's forthcoming
visit to China would result in "concrete achievements" in promoting
world peace and expanding cooperation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
