<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Southeast Asia Remains Vital for China's Trade (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, April 27 (Xinhua) -- The changing global market
provides fresh opportunities for economic and trade cooperation
between China and the Southeast Asian nations, even though
purchasing power in Southeast Asia has weakened in the wake of the
regional financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
The assiduous endeavors of China and the Southeast Asian
nations to promote mutual trade is reflected in the activities at
the 83rd Guangzhou Export Commodities Trade Fair (GECTF), now
being held in this capital of south China's Guangdong Province.
</P>
<P>
Ben Ang, a general merchandise trader from the Philippines,
said that, despite a shortage of money, people in the Philippines
still have a strong demand for daily-use articles, and Chinese
products are welcomed for their high quality and low prices compared
with goods from other countries.
</P>
<P>
"Half of the products in my shop come from China," Ang said.
</P>
<P>
A majority of businessmen from Southeast Asia attending the GECTF
shared Ang's view. High-quality and inexpensive daily-use and industrial
products from China have become the primary choice of customers in
Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
As traditional markets for China, the country's exports to
Southeast Asian nations account for seven percent of its total
trade volume. However, the Asian financial crisis since the latter
half of last year has caused a devaluation of currencies in some
nations, resulting in a fund shortage and restrictions on imports.
</P>
<P>
But Zhou Shijian, a Chinese expert on foreign trade, predicted
good prospects for economic growth in Southeast Asia upon
industrial restructuring there.
</P>
<P>
The financial crisis in Southeast Asia offers not only a
challenge but also opportunities for China's exports, said Zhou,
who is also vice-president of the China Chamber of Commerce of
Importers and Exporters of Hardwares.
</P>
<P>
He suggested that Chinese enterprises should readjust their
export mix in accordance with the special requirements of this
region, cut production costs and increase competitiveness, in a
bid to preserve these traditional markets.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
