<HEADLINE> China's Lawmakers Urge Spread of Fire-Control Knowledge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 27 (Xinhua) -- China's lawmakers recommended
that people be made more aware of the necessity for and ways to
accomplish fire control when they deliberated the draft of the
country's first Law on Fire Control here today.
</P>
<P>
Many legislators said that the law should put more stress on
fire prevention.
</P>
<P>
The law should contain fire-prevention rules for residential
buildings, said Liu Zhongyi, a member of the Standing Committee of
the National People's Congress (NPC).
</P>
<P>
Ye Shuhua and Wang Youhui, also members of the NPC Standing
Committee, suggested that radio and television stations broadcast
programs concerning fire control and fire safety tips.
</P>
<P>
A group of Japanese people survived a conflagration in a Xi'an
hotel a few years ago because they were aware of what to do in
case of fire, whereas many Chinese lives were lost in the same
fire, Ye said.
</P>
<P>
Many members of the NPC Standing Committee suggested that the
ongoing second session of the NPC Standing Committee pass the law
draft.
</P>
<P>
In addition, some members urged the removal of factories where
the potential danger of explosion is present, including
storehouses and oil depots, which are near downtown areas.
</P>
<P>
Wang Yongning and Yang Zhenhuai called for the upgrading of the
equipment used by Chinese fire brigades.
</P>
<P>
The country should forbid the opening of entertainment
facilities, which might easily cause fires, near historical and
cultural sites such as museums, archives and libraries, Fan
Jingyi suggested.
</P>
<P>
The 28th session of the NPC Standing Committee held a
preliminary deliberation of the law draft in October last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
