<HEADLINE> Southeast Asia Remains Vital for China's Trade (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The number of businessmen from Southeast Asia visiting the
present GECTF has decreased by 20 percent over previous fairs. And
many of them demand low prices and their orders are small. So far,
the transaction volume with Southeast Asia is 300 million US
dollars-worth, much less than at previous fairs.
</P>
<P>
Li Yueling, general manager of the Export Department of the
China Petrochemicals International Co., has signed a contract
worth one million US dollars for the export of paraffin wax.
</P>
<P>
"Trade partners in China and Southeast Asia should join efforts
to tide over this difficult period," Li said.
</P>
<P>
Chind Satukijchai, a frequent Thailand visitor to the GECTF,
said that some Southeast Asian nations have a great demand for raw
materials, semi-finished products and spare parts to accelerate
their processing industries. Chinese products are quite
competitive in terms of assortment of goods and low prices.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Southeast Asia may benefit from the devaluation of
Southeast Asian currencies in importing rice and palm oil.
</P>
<P>
China's imports from Southeast Asia in the first quarter of
this year rose 7.3 percent compared with the same period of last
year, far exceeding the country's overall import growth rate of
2.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government is expected to encourage domestic
enterprises to adopt a more flexible approach to trade with
countries in the region, such as by conducting barter trade.
</P>
