<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF Predicts Moderate Rebound of Crisis-Hit Economies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 27 (Xinhua) -- The International Monetary Fund
(IMF) has predicted moderate rebound of the economies which were
hit by the financial crisis starting mid-1997.
</P>
<P>
The latest version of the World Economic Outlook (WEO) released
by the IMF earlier this month predicts that confidence should
recover gradually during 1998, paving the way for a "moderate
rebound in growth in 1999 and solid recovery by 2000" of the
crisis-hit economies.
</P>
<P>
Presenting the WEO here on Monday, Flemming Larsen, deputy
director of the IMF's Research Department, said because of the
seriousness of the crisis, "we may not see swift recovery" of the
crisis-hit economies, and "it may take a little longer -- at least
a year, maybe two years -- and may not get to the historical
growth rate (before the crisis)."
</P>
<P>
The WEO says countering the potential for new crises is a
considerable challenge that needs to be met through increased
vigilance of national policymakers and private investors.
</P>
<P>
"A key task for policymakers is to identify weaknesses and
imbalances early enough to be able to address them before crises
erupt, and the development and monitoring of early-warning
indicators of vulnerability may be helpful in this regard," the
WEO says.
</P>
<P>
In assessing the crisis, the WEO says the financial turmoil has
abated since January 1998, and markets have partially recovered
from their troughs. However, currency and asset values in the
countries involved have been left far below precrisis levels, and
considerable uncertainty remains about the resolution of the
crisis and its global repercussions.
</P>
<P>
The WEO warns there are "clearly downside risks" although the
threat to global growth from the Asian crisis still appears to be
limited.
</P>
<P>
Part of the answer seems to be that these countries became
victims of their own success, which had led domestic and foreign
investors to underestimate the countries' economic weaknesses, the
WEO says.
</P>
<P>
To contain the economic damage caused by the crisis, it says,
the countries directly affected have needed to implement
corrective measures, and the international community led by the
IMF has provided financial support for policy programs in the
countries worst hit.
</P>
<P>
The WEO noted that monetary policy must be kept sufficiently
firm to resist excessive currency depreciation, and that
weaknesses in the financial sector require particularly urgent
attention, including a clearly announced reform agenda in each
case.
</P>
<P>
The WEO says improvements in public and corporate governance
and a strengthening of transparency and accountability are also
essential.
</P>
<P>
The IMF report points out that financial markets in China have
remained relatively unaffected by the Asian crisis, reflecting the
country's relatively closed capital account -- capital flows
consist primarily of direct investment as well as its large
foreign exchange reserves.
</P>
<P>
According to the WEO, Latin America and other regions have
weathered the Asian storm by implementing immediate policy
tightening to help ease their own pressures. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980427.0072 </DOCNO>
