<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU FMs Agree to Lift "Label" From China, Russia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, April 27 (Xinhua) -- The foreign ministers of the
European Union (EU) agreed on Monday to remove the "non-market
economy" status label from China and Russia.
</P>
<P>
At their Luxembourg council meeting, the foreign ministers
reached the agreement which is expected to update anti-dumping
rules that protect the 15-nation union against unfair pricing of
imports.
</P>
<P>
Sir Leon Brittan said that China and Russia have made real
economic progress toward becoming market economies.
</P>
<P>
The European Commission vice-president described the agreement
as a sensible and practical reform. The adoption of the reform
brings the EU anti-dumping rules up to date, he said.
</P>
<P>
Commission officials added that the removal of China and Russia
from the non-market economy list reflects the substantial advances
made by both countries toward market economy conditions.
</P>
<P>
The EU non-market economy list came into existence in the 1950s.
</P>
<P>
The officials also said the EU move recognizes China's and
Russia's efforts to transform their economies by allowing domestic
price information to be used in anti-dumping investigations if the
existence of market economy conditions can be demonstrated.
</P>
<P>
Under EU rules, dumping occurs when a manufacturer sells goods
on an export market at a price lower than its normal value.
</P>
<P>
China and Russia are both important trading partners with the
EU. EU-China trade has increased more than 20 times since 1978.
</P>
<P>
The Asian country has become EU's third largest non-European
trading partner, with the volume of bilateral trade increasing
from 25,000 million ECUs to 45,000 million ECUs between 1992 and
1996.
</P>
<P>
Trade between EU and Russia has also increased dramatically,
from 17,600 million ECUs in 1992 to 42,400 million ECUs in 1996.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980427.0079 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK's Ting Kau Bridge to Be Opened to Traffic in May </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Ting Kau Bridge, the longest
cable-stayed bridge in Hong Kong, will be opened to traffic on May
6 this year to help relieve growing traffic between the northwest
"New Territories" and the urban areas.
</P>
<P>
This was announced by the Transport Department here Monday.
</P>
<P>
Design and construction of Ting Kau Bridge began in September
1994 with a total contract value of up to 1.738 billion HK dollars
(222.82 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The 1,177-meter-Ting Kau Bridge forms a vital part of Route
Three trunk road network including Tai Lam Tunnel which is
scheduled to be opened in a few weeks later.
</P>
<P>
The bridge comprises two carriage ways, each having three
traffic lanes and a hard shoulder.
</P>
<P>
A government spokesman said the bridge provides a convenient
and direct access for residents in the northwest "New Territories"
not only to Tung Chung on Lantau Island but also to the new
airport at Chek Lap Kok. 
</P>
</TEXT>
