<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HKMA to Continue Improving Sound Banking Sector </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 27 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong Monetary
Authority (HKMA) Monday pledged to "continue to improve the
soundness of the banking sector; enhance the transparency of the
financial system; and promote the development of a deep and liquid
debt market."
</P>
<P>
Joseph Yam, chief executive of the HKMA, said in the 1997
Annual Report of the HKMA published here Monday that the year 1997
was one of the most eventful and significant chapters in the
financial history of Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank and International Monetary Fund (IMF) Annual
Meetings provided a most timely opportunity for the international
financial community to witness the successful political transition
of Hong Kong as a vital international financial center, he said.
</P>
<P>
Noting that the most serious currency turmoil in Asia dominated
the last quarter of the year, he said that however, "Hong Kong was
fortunate and with good reasons to be the least and the last to be
affected."
</P>
<P>
Yam attributed the fact that the Hong Kong dollar has weathered
the regional financial turmoil relatively unscathed compared to
other Asian currencies to the numerous reforms of the monetary
system introduced over the last 14 years to strengthen the
currency system.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, the performance of the Exchange Fund
and the Land Fund was also satisfactory despite the extremely
volatile market in 1997.
</P>
<P>
On the banking front, Yam said, limited exposure to the Asian
region explained why banks in Hong Kong have been able to stand up
well against the currency turmoil.
</P>
<P>
To prepare Hong Kong's banking sector for the next millennium,
the HKMA has started a strategic study to address the challenges
ahead, he noted.
</P>
<P>
Yam said lessons learned from 1997 are clear: The HKMA will
have to remain highly vigilant and should be proactive and
preemptive rather than reactive. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980427.0082 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-27 13:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mazen, Ross Discuss Israeli Position on Pullback </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Deputy head of the Palestinian
National Authority (PNA) Mahmoud Abbas (Abu Mazen) met here
Monday with the United States peace envoy Dennis Ross to discuss
the dispute over Israeli redeployment in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Mazen and Ross held the one-hour meeting in the King David
Hotel behind closed doors. The meeting was a follow-up to that
held Sunday night in Gaza between Ross and PNA leader Yasser
Arafat.
</P>
<P>
Ross, accompanied by U.S. Assistant Secretary of State Martin
Indyk, arrived here Saturday and had already held two meetings
with Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu before holding
talks with Arafat.
</P>
<P>
His mission here is to prepare for the May 4 meetings in
London, where U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright will
hold separate talks with Netanyahu and Arafat in an attempt to
solve the dispute over redeployment.
</P>
<P>
After meeting with Mazen, Ross left through a back door to
evade reporters waiting at the lobby of the hotel. This was seen
as a sign that he made little progress in bridging the huge gap
between the Israelis and Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Leading Palestinian negotiator Saeb Erekat told reporters that
the two sides held "extensive discussions" on the Israeli
redeployment, the joint interim committees and other issues.
</P>
<P>
Erekat said that Mazen assured Ross and Indyk that the PNA
wanted to move forward with the peace process, but it demanded
the Americans "immediately move to the substance" on the
redeployment issue by stopping Israel's game-playing.
</P>
<P>
"Time is crucial. It's time to move, and we should not
continue following the game of Mr. Netanyahu's, because wasting
time is not in the benefit of anyone," Erekat said.
</P>
<P>
Erekat said the Palestinian side hoped to see the publication
of the U.S. plan calling for a 13.1 percent Israeli withdrawal
during the London talks. The PNA has accepted the plan in a
compromise move and is urging the U.S. to pressure Israel to
soften its position of intransigency.
</P>
<P>
So far Netanyahu has rejected the U.S. plan and tried to
disuade Washington from making known the plan for fear of its
ensuing pressure on Israel. Israel's rightwing government has
declared that it could only accomondate a 9 percent pullback at
best.
</P>
<P>
Besides the size of the second redeployment, another sticking
point in the Israeli-Palestinian dispute is that Israel hopes to
gain the U.S. support to its call for abolishing the third
redeployment and integrate it into the final-status talks.
</P>
<P>
The PNA has rejected the Israeli idea, insisting that Israel
must continue to carry out the third troop redeployment before
proceeding to talks for a permanent Israeli-Palestinian
settlement, in accordance with the Hebron accord signed early last
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980427.0083 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tourist Arrivals to Macao Drop </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Tourist arrivals to Macao during
the first three months of 1998 dropped 10.9 percent from the same
period last year, latest official statistics show.
</P>
<P>
Figures released by the Macao Census and Statistics Department
on Monday show that the arrivals added up to 1,784,117 between
January and March, down 10.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
In March alone, the number of visitors to Macao dropped 23.4
percent to 578,181 in March 1998 from 713,476 in the same month in
1997.
</P>
<P>
Although the number of Hong Kong visitors, which account for 70
percent, increased 2.5 percent, those from the Republic of Korea,
Japan, Europe and Southeast Asia plummeted as much as 86 percent
in the first three months.
</P>
<P>
The less arrivals were believed to be connected with the
devaluation of currencies in Southeast Asia nations in the wake of
the financial crisis there.
</P>
<P>
Tourism is a leading economic sector for the territory of
420,000 population. Last year Macao received some seven million
visitors, down 14 percent from the previous year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
