<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Plenary Session of HK/US Economic Cooperation Committee </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 27 (Xinhua) -- The first year of the Hong Kong
Special Administrative Region (HKSAR) has been a success and the
principle of "one country, two systems" is now an established
reality, the HK/U.S. and the U.S./HK Economic Cooperation
Committees said Monday.
</P>
<P>
According to a joint communique issued after the one-day joint
plenary session held here, members of the committees also said
that Hong Kong's economy had been affected by fallout from the
financial and economic crises suffered by other economies in the
Asian region.
</P>
<P>
They agreed that the HKSAR government's unwavering commitment
to the Kong Kong/US dollar link had helped to stabilize the local
situation and retain international business confidence in Hong
Kong. They all recognized the importance of a strong and stable
Renminbi, China's currency.
</P>
<P>
The committee members agreed that the distinctive and
predictable characteristics of Hong Kong's economy, including its
stable currency, huge foreign reserves, unrestricted movement of
capital, free flows of information, transparent administrative and
legal systems, had enabled it to better withstand fluctuations
elsewhere in the region, the communique said.
</P>
<P>
These strong fundamentals were also the reason "why Hong Kong
continues to be regarded by U.S. companies as an attractive
business location and good commercial partner," it said.
</P>
<P>
The committee members were particularly encouraged by the
increase in contacts between the United States and China,
including the exchanges of presidential visits, the communique
noted.
</P>
<P>
In the light of these positive developments, the communique
said, the committees anticipated that China's MFN status would be
renewed this year, and that China's application for WTO entry
would also continue to make progress.
</P>
<P>
The plenary session of the committees has received messages of
support from Chief Executive Tung Chee Hwa of the HKSAR and U.S.
Secretary of Commerce William Daley.
</P>
<P>
The committee members are scheduled to proceed to Shanghai on
Tuesday and Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The HK/US &AMP; US/HK Economic Cooperation Committees meet once a
year. The next session will be held in the United States in 1999.
</P>
</TEXT>
