<HEADLINE> Replica of Emperors' Throne to Be Auctioned </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 27 (Xinhua) -- A replica of the throne used by
generations of Chinese emperors will be auctioned to buyers
from at home and abroad at the end of May, sources at the
Beijing Auction Company said here today.
</P>
<P>
Starting today, this precious artistic work will be on show
for 20 days at the Tianlun Dynasty Hotel here.
</P>
<P>
The reproduction is a copy of the throne in the Hall of Great
Harmony in the Palace Museum, located in the center of Beijing.
</P>
<P>
According to Wu Lianzhong, manager of the company's Artistic
Works Department, the duplicated treasure is the only artistic
work made under the supervision of experts from the Palace Museum.
</P>
<P>
An appraisal conducted by the Beijing Administration of State
Assets shows that the replica is worth more than 185 million yuan
(about 22.3 million US dollars).
</P>
<P>
A total of 86 artists, including specialists employed at the
Palace Museum, spent six years on the work, using 28 tons of
high-purity gold and over 3,000 pieces of rare natural gemstones.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the highly ornamented pedestal is made of rare red
sandalwood.
</P>
<P>
The replica, 128 cm long, 120 cm wide and 73 cm high, has more
than depictions of 2,000 dragons on it, including some 600 dragons
less than 2.5 mm in length.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
