<HEADLINE> Malaysia Sets Up Fund for Low-, Medium-Cost Houses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia Monday announced
the establishment of a Special Fund for Low- and Medium-Cost
Houses, which will begin operation on May 1, 1998.
</P>
<P>
Bank Negara (state bank) Malaysia, the central bank, will
provide funding facility amounting to 1 billion ringgit (265.251
million U.S. dollars) under the scheme, the bank said in a press
release Monday.
The money is to be channeled directly to financial institutions as
loans for housing developers building houses costing 150,000
ringgit (about 40,000 dollars) and below.
</P>
<P>
The bank added that the establishment of the fund is part of
the ongoing process to ensure the availability of affordable
houses to meet the needs of low- and middle-income groups given
the current economic and financial environment and tight monetary
stance of the state bank.
</P>
<P>
The latest facility is in addition to the 1 billion ringgit
(265.251 million dollars) worth of funds announced in October last
year, which were provided by Petronas when it subscribed to bonds
in Syarikat Perumahan Negara (SPN) (National Housing Corporation).
</P>
<P>
The central bank said the extension of this facility should not
be deemed expansionary on the monetary aggregates, emphasizing
that the credit target of 15 percent as announced earlier will
remain unchanged.
</P>
<P>
The annual rate of loan growth of the banking system sands at
17 percent at present, according to the bank. 
</P>
</TEXT>
