<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Endorses Social Protection Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, April 27 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission adopted
its 1997 social welfare report which monitors progress achieved
in social welfare objectives within the European Union.
</P>
<P>
The report, the third following the 1993 and 1995 editions,
examines demographic, social and economic developments and the
changing context in which social welfare systems in the union
operate.
</P>
<P>
It also analyzes expenditures on social welfare protection in
EU member states and reviews their contribution to reducing
disparities in income between households.
</P>
<P>
The report reviewed the major changes which have been made to
social welfare systems across the 15-nation union in recent years,
focusing on the period since 1995.
</P>
<P>
The report emphasized the operation of unemployment
compensation systems, the policies toward retirement and toward
reversing the trend of people to retire before reaching the
official pension age, the action to contain the growing cost of
health care while safeguarding the quality of service, and
long-term care for those who are infirm or too ill to look after
themselves.
</P>
<P>
The foreign ministers of the European Union recommended in July
1992 to merge social protection objectives and policies, and the
union started to monitor the convergence via biennial reports the
following year.
</P>
<P>
European Commissioner Padraig Flynn, responsible for employment
and social affairs, stressed that benefit systems need to be
reviewed and adapted to ensure they actively support employability.
</P>
<P>
"Social protection can help achieve other aims such as
developing entrepreneurship, encouraging adaptability of
businesses and their employees, and strengthening policies for
equal opportunities," Flynn added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980427.0095 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Project Launched to Aid Poor Rural Teachers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 27 (Xinhua) -- The China Charity Federation (CCF)
started its "Candlelight Project" today to raise donations to
help poor teachers in rural China improve their lives and
professional skills.
</P>
<P>
The project, with a fund under the same name, plans to collect
two million yuan (about 241,000 U.S. dollars) in donations this
year, said Zhang Wanxin, chairman of the board of the project and
vice-chairman of the CCF.
</P>
<P>
The donations will be used to provide training materials for
3,000 schools in 300 poor counties, subsidize 1,000 poor
teachers in rural areas, and reward a group of outstanding rural
teachers who are not paid by the government but by local people,
he said.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that China has a total of three million rural
teachers, who are usually paid tiny salaries by the local
people and who make up about 60 percent of the total number of
rural teachers.
</P>
<P>
They provide education to one third of China's primary and
middle school students, who amount to 20 percent of the world's
total but only receive 0.78 percent of the world's total
funds for education.
</P>
<P>
Some rural teachers are living in extremely poor conditions,
and many ambitious ones have left their positions for better-paid
jobs. This, along with the factor that the professional skills of
rural teachers need improvement, has hindered the development of
rural education in China, said Zhang.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the "Candlelight Project" will be as
beneficial to rural education as "Project Hope", which helps
poor children in rural areas to go to school.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
