<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Intra-Afghan Talks Make "Good Progress" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, April 27 (Xinhua) -- The on-going intra-Afghan talks
have made "good progress" as Afghanistan's Islamic Taliban and the
rival Northern Alliance Monday agreed on a four-point agenda
including the formation of the Ulema (religious scholar)
Commission and ceasefire.
</P>
<P>
This was announced by Ibrahim Saleh Bakar, assistant secretary
general of the Organization of the Islamic Conference, Monday
afternoon after the Joint Steering Committee, which consists of
five Taliban and nine alliance delegates, concluded its morning
session on the second day of the talks.
</P>
<P>
He said the talks, the first face-to-face encounter between the
two Afghan rivals in more than a year, made "good progress" and
the two sides have agreed on the four-point agenda.
</P>
<P>
Bakar said that the two sides will continue to talk at 4 p.m.
Monday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The agenda, he said, includes the consideration of matters
relating to the Ulema Commission, ceasefire between the two sides
and the release of prisoners of war of both sides, the modalities
for lifting the blockade to central Afghanistan and allowing
humanitarian aid to move freely in the country, and the date and
venue of the next meeting of the Steering Committee.
</P>
<P>
James Ngobi, acting head of the United Nations Special Mission
on Afghanistan, described the atmosphere of Monday's talks between
the two sides as "good" and said "they have made some progress."
</P>
<P>
The talks, which are being jointly sponsored by the U.N. and
the OIC, started on Sunday morning but failed to make any progress
on the first day as the Taliban and the Northern Alliance could
not reach an agreement on the agenda.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban, who now control two-thirds of Afghanistan,
insisted that the formation of the Ulema Commission be the only
topic of the agenda while the Northern Alliance, which holds the
rest one third, wanted to include ceasefire and exchange of
prisoners of war.
</P>
<P>
However, the two sides agreed on Sunday that the talks should
be concluded within three days if possible and not later than five
days. They also decided that the decision of the meeting will be
taken by consensus and not by voting, and if there is lack of
consensus on any matter under discussion, it would be referred to
their respective leadership or be postponed till the next meeting
of the Steering Committee.
</P>
<P>
The Ulema Commission proposed by the Taliban would decide the
future political set-up in Kabul if and when formed. The Joint
Steering Committee is yet another attempt to iron out differences
between the Taliban and the Northern Alliance after the former
rejected the latter's first Ulema list in February. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
