<HEADLINE> Turkey Rejects Greek Sovereignty Claim to Aegean </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Turkey Monday rejected Greece's
claim of sovereignty over the uninhabited islets in the Aegean Sea
and reiterated that the status of those islets will have to be
decided through negotiations between Turkey and Greece.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Foreign Ministry deputy spokesman Sermet Atacanli told
a weekly news briefing that the Greek government should not take
it for granted that these islets belong to Greece.
</P>
<P>
Greece attempted recently to include these islets under the
name of Greek territory in an environment program of the European
Union (EU), said Atacanli.
</P>
<P>
"As we said before, this is not something new. Greece's
territorial claims to these undecided islands are unacceptable to
Turkey," Atacanli said.
</P>
<P>
He said that the Turkish government has been in contact with
the EU regarding this matter and hopes that the European bloc
could prevent Athens from doing this.
</P>
<P>
Turkey and Greece have been at odds for long over the
sovereignty of these islets. In early 1996, their dispute over an
islet, called Kardak in Turkish and Imia in Greek, brought the two
countries to the brink of war. 
</P>
</TEXT>
