<HEADLINE> Higher Electricity Prices in China to Cover Environmental Costs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 27 (Xinhua) -- An official from the China Power
Corp. said here today that China is drafting regulations and
methods to further raise the price of electricity.
</P>
<P>
However, he said that price of electricity for agriculture use
will not increase by a large margin, while the price of
electricity for rural areas and industries will fully depend on
the market.
</P>
<P>
China will turn all power enterprises into companies that will
operate as commercial entities, the official said.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the belief that free-market competition is needed
for sustainable growth in the power industry and that producers
will raise prices to cover expenses of environmental protection if
the electricity market is fully deregulated.
</P>
<P>
China is giving top priority to hydro-electric power, proper
development of coal-fired electricity and the use of clean-coal
technology, he said. Market competition will favor large-scale
power companies that run at a relatively lower cost and force
seriously polluting small coal-fired power plants out of business,
he added.
</P>
<P>
He said that stopping price controls will also promote
large-scale enterprises to use clean-coal technology, and that his
own company will cover the cost of adding environmental-protection
technology by raising the price of electricity.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the Chinese government is prudent in
raising electricity prices. The present rise is of a compensatory
nature for power companies. He said that the administrative
authorities of the power industry and prices and auditing
authorities are carefully drafting the procedures of raising
prices.
</P>
<P>
China's potential water power is equal to 1.5 times the total
power-generating capacity of the country at present. In the 10
years after 2000, China will increase its hydropower capacity by
80 million kilowatts.
</P>
<P>
Sichuan Province plans to build the largest clean-coal plant in
the world with technology that will greatly reduce the amount of
sulphur and nitrogen gas emissions.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
