<HEADLINE> Zambia Calls for Dismantling Regional Customs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Zambia has called for dismantling
the Southern African Customs Union (SACU) to ensure free regional
trade and increase Zambia's foreign exchange earnings.
</P>
<P>
The Lusaka Chamber of Commerce and Industry (LCCI) has urged
the Southern African Development Community (SADC) to work toward
the immediate dismantling of SACU, Times of Zambia paper reported
Monday.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper quoted LCCI Vice Chairman for Trade Henry
Chipewo as saying that here at the weekend that the delayed
dissolution of SACU contributes significantly to his country's
unstable exchange rate because manufacturers have limited export
market in the southern African region.
</P>
<P>
"Our members cannot export to the SACU member countries which
include South Africa, Namibia, Mozambique and Botswana when
manufacturers in these countries freely exported their goods and
services to Zambia," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said dismantling SACU will lead to free trade in the region
thus increasing Zambia's export and foreign exchange earnings.
</P>
<P>
SACU is a trade barrier in the region whose removal requires
concerted efforts from SADC member countries, he said.
</P>
<P>
Chipewo urged the Export Board of Zambia to support all
efforts made by LCCI to increase exports because the board
derives its strength from exporters. 
</P>
</TEXT>
