<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beida Plays Unique Role in Modern China's History (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 27 (Xinhua) -- The prestigious Beijing
University, also known as Beida, has played a unique role in
China's modern and contemporary history. That is the main reason
why the university's centennial celebration has drawn so much
attention nationwide, experts say.
</P>
<P>
The celebration activities, on an unprecedented scale, include
a meeting of 10,000 people at the Great Hall of the People, and an
evening of entertainment which will be attended by a large number
of Chinese artists as well as teachers and students of the
university.
</P>
<P>
China has also decided to issue a set of commemorative stamps
for the university's 100th anniversary on May 4 when most of the
activities will take place.
</P>
<P>
"All these are because Beijing University's role in China's
history cannot be replaced," said Chen Pingyuan, professor with
the Chinese Department of Beijing University.
</P>
<P>
"Currently, Beijing University is not ranked among the
world's first-class universities, but no other university in the
world has played a role as important to their national
rejuvenation and national progress as Beijing University," he
added.
</P>
<P>
He said that Beijing University was the birthplace of the May
4th Movement of 1919, an anti-imperialist, anti-feudal, political
and cultural movement in China. Influenced by the October
Revolution in Russia, the movement was led by intellectuals with
rudiments of Communist ideology.
</P>
<P>
Marxism was first disseminated in the university, and the
university was one of the most important revolutionary bases for
the Chinese Communist Party in its early days, said Chen, who has
studied the university's history for years.
</P>
<P>
According to Chen, the Vernacular Movement (1917-1919)
originated in the university, which was the cradle of China's new
culture, and the vernacular later developed into the commonly used
written language in China.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
