<HEADLINE> German Delegation to Visit Iran for Better Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Iranian Foreign Minister Kamal
Kharrazi announced here on Monday that a German high-ranking
delegation would visit Iran in the near future to defrost the
relations between Tehran and Bonn.
</P>
<P>
He told reporters at a press conference that the forthcoming
visit of German officials would be at the director general level.
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister gave no further details of the visit.
</P>
<P>
However, he said that the visit would have positive impact on
Tehran-Bonn ties, which have become "better" following the return of
European ambassadors to Tehran in November last year.
</P>
<P>
Relations between Iran and Germany were strained in April last
year after a Berlin court ruled that Iranian leaders were behind
a terrorist assassination against four Iranian Kurdish rebel
leaders in Berlin.
</P>
<P>
The court verdict provoked members of the European Union (EU)
to withdraw their ambassadors from Tehran. They returned to Tehran
after the EU reached a deal with Iran over the political row in
November.
</P>
<P>
Despite the detente between the EU and Iran, the Bonn-Tehran
reapproachment was delayed by the case of the German citizen
Helmut Hoffer, who was sentenced to death in Iran on charges of
having illegal sexual relationship with an Iranian Muslim woman.
</P>
<P>
German Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel warned that Bonn-Tehran
ties would be damaged if Iran carried out the death sentence on
Hoffer. Iran claimed that the case was reviewed in Iran according
to normal judicial procedures.
</P>
<P>
The German Parliamentarian Gunger Verhugen paid a two-day
visit to Tehran last week to convince the Iranian authorities to
release Hoffer in order to repair the bilateral relations. But no
concrete achievement was reached during the visit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
