<HEADLINE> S. Africa Beefs Up Security for Telecom Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 27 (Xinhua) -- A massive security
operation involving police and traffic officers in Pretoria and
Johannesburg will be set in motion when Africa's largest
telecommunications conference will be held here next week.
</P>
<P>
More than 40 telecommunications ministers and their
delegations are expected to attend the week-long Africa Telecom
98 Forum and Exhibition.
</P>
<P>
About 100 large buses will be used to transport the estimated
6,000 participants from their hotels to the conference venue and
back, the organizers said.
</P>
<P>
Twenty police stations between Johannesburg and Pretoria have
been mobilized to ensure that criminal elements have no
opportunity to mug, attack or hijack guests.
</P>
<P>
Policemen would be asked to work overtime and those on leave
would be recalled to provide security for the visitors, Inspector
Nati de Jagger said at the weekend.
</P>
<P>
Car and foot patrols by uniformed and plain clothes policemen
will be visible along the route and in the vicinity of the 40
hotels where the guests will be staying.
</P>
<P>
All traffic departments and emergency services will also be on
24-hour call. 
</P>
</TEXT>
