<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ivory Trade Rampant in Dar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Illegal trading of ivory
still runs rampant in the Tanzanian capital of Dar es Salaam
despite the ban of the government and international community on
poaching of elephants, Daily Mail has revealed.
</P>
<P>
According to investigations by the Dar es Salaam-based
newspaper, ivory is transported into the city through various
channels and then sold, or carved by craftsmen and exported
abroad, especially to the Far East.
</P>
<P>
There are people in Kariakoo, Mwenge and other areas of the
city who buy the ivory, with each kilogram priced at 12,000
shillings (about 18 U.S. Dollars) at present, an unnamed illegal
ivory dealer disclosed to the paper.
</P>
<P>
In the Mwenge Carvers Village, the ivory is bought, carved
immediately and sold as a finished product, the dealer said.
</P>
<P>
Most of the ivory products were purchased by women and
foreigners, the source said, adding that women buy earrings,
bangles and other ornaments for trading elsewhere in the city,
while candle holders, chess pieces and carvings of Madonna are
favored by foreigners.
</P>
<P>
Buyers were numerous, and delay in selling occurred only when
a price was not agreed upon, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said there was plenty of ivory in rural areas, especially
in the Kilombero District some 200 kilometers southwest of the
capital.
</P>
<P>
Dealers get ivory from farmers who live near the Selous Game
Reserve, the world's largest. The farmers use homemade guns to
kill elephants and bury the tusks in the fields, waiting for
buyers to come.
</P>
<P>
"When we want to buy ivory," he said, "all we do is to go to
this area and ask around. You will be surprised with the amount
of offers you will get within a short time."
</P>
<P>
"I know what I am doing is not right but some big shots are
doing things which are even worse," he said, and added that it is
very easy to bring ivory into Dar es Salaam as long as one has
"the nerves."
</P>
<P>
He said a small consignment of ivory can be packed carefully
in a brief case, a sack or anything else with few chances of
being caught by the police.
</P>
<P>
If the amount is big, he said, one may use vehicles which will
not be subject to police check, such as army vehicles.
</P>
<P>
Big dealers even use containers to export raw ivory, he said,
noting that they pack ivory in containers along with other cargo
for export.
</P>
<P>
Sometimes the ivory is sent in dhows to the Zanzibar isles,
where shipping ivory abroad is even safer than in Dar es Salaam.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980427.0112 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kuala Lumpur Stocks Close Lower </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Share prices on the Kuala
Lumpur Stock Exchange closed lower Monday in line with falls at
other regional bourses.
</P>
<P>
At the close, the 100-quality stocks Composite Index fell 14.32
points to 620.79, the all-share Emas Index erased 3.17 points to
close at 156.39 and the Industrial Index fell 17.84 points to
1,147.43 while the Second Board Index slipped 2.38 points to
135.23.
</P>
<P>
Losers led gainers 505 to 123 with 139 unchanged and 167 others
untraded.
</P>
<P>
The day's total turnover stood at 105.328 million shares valued
at 215.833 million ringgit (57.25 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The Main Board volume rose to 93.962 million shares worth
199.078 million ringgit (52.806 million dollars) from last
Friday's 85.918 million shares worth 182.067 million ringgit
(48.294 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
The Second Board turnover fell to 11.366 million shares valued
at 16.755 million ringgit (4.444 million dollars) against 12.038
million shares worth 17.287 million ringgit (4.585 million
dollars) last Friday.
</P>
<P>
Off-market deals totaled 112.347 million valued at 254.033
million ringgit (67.383 million dollars) compared with 5.355
million shares worth 18.241 million ringgit (4.838 million
dollars) last Friday.
</P>
<P>
Selling activity dominated the market since early trade as
players emerged to dispose of their shares, ahead of the holiday
Tuesday for the Islamic New Year.
</P>
<P>
The market would also be closed on Friday, May 1, for the Labor
Day holiday.
</P>
<P>
A dealer said the weaknesses of the local currency which ended
at 3.7740/890 to the U.S. dollar against Friday's close of 3.7550
also spooked investors amid the absence of fresh leads.  
</P>
</TEXT>
