<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia to Strengthen Tax Laws for Foreign Firms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Australia announced on Monday
its plans to strengthen tax laws for foreign companies
transferring ownership of property or mining rights in Australia.
</P>
<P>
Australian Federal Treasurer Peter Costello said the government
would tighten a loophole allowing non-residents to escape tax on
profits from the sale of real (commercial) property and mining
rights through a chain of holding companies or trusts.
</P>
<P>
He said in a statement that the government would amend the
International Tax Agreements Act 1953 to clarify the
interpretation of the alienation of property articles in
Australia's Double Tax Agreements (DTAs).
</P>
<P>
The move followed a full federal court finding that real
property held by a non-resident through a chain of companies did
not fall within the terms of provisions of the
Australia-Netherlands DTA.
</P>
<P>
Costello said the decision had implications for all of
Australia's DTAs and highlighted chances for non-residents to
escape Australian taxes on profits from the sale of real property
and mining rights in Australia by the use of a chain of holding
companies or trusts.
</P>
<P>
"The government has therefore decided to amend the law to
ensure it applies to profits arising from the indirect alienation
of real property by a non-resident after midday ... today," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Costello said countries with which Australia had concluded DTAs
were being advised of the proposed action. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
