<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Over 20m Nigerians Infected with Liver Disease </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 27 (Xinhua) -- At least 20 million Nigerians may
be suffering from the liver disease commonly known as hepatitis
B, according to the West African Society of Gastroenterology
(WASG).
</P>
<P>
The society, which gave the warning in a communique issued
after the 12th national conference of its Nigeria chapter, also
identified viral hepatitis as the major cause of chronic liver
disease in the country and other west African countries.
</P>
<P>
According to WASG, it has been established that hepatitis B
virus is the cause of hepatocellular carcinoma, a malignant and
terminal disease of the liver, while statistics show that the
disease is the commonest cancer among Nigerians.
</P>
<P>
The communique expressed displeasure that there was a dearth
of trained professionals in the diagnosis of liver diseases.
</P>
<P>
"Diagnostic facilities are inadequate and there is poor
reporting of chronic liver diseases, making it difficult to
determine accurately the burden of this disease," it said, quoted
by the Daily Times Monday.
</P>
<P>
Most of the drugs needed for the treatment of chronic liver
disease were either not locally available or unaffordable, it
noted.
</P>
<P>
The WASG communique warned against the use of traditional
means such as scarification marks and tattoos in treating the
disease.
</P>
<P>
It called for an improved reporting system of the notifiable
disease especially viral hepatitis by an improvement of the
existing health management information system.
</P>
<P>
It also appealed to the health ministries to incorporate the
education of the masses on the need to avoid harmful
socio-cultural practices to stem the tide of increasing
incidences of the diseases. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
