<HEADLINE> Iran: No Need to Resume Ties with Washington </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Iranian Foreign Minister Kamal
Kharrazi reiterated on Monday that Iran still sees no need to
re-establish brokened Iran-U.S. relations unless Washington
changes its hostile policies toward Tehran.
</P>
<P>
Responding to former U.S. assistant secretary of state Richard
Murphy's recent call for "meaningful and clear official exchanges"
between the two sides, Kharrazi said that "we has not seen any
need to do so."
</P>
<P>
He told reporters at a press conference that Iran rejected the
resumption of relations because of Washington's failure to bring
any change into its animosity-dominated policies toward Iran.
</P>
<P>
Citing a U.S. decision to expand Persian language broadcasting
service to Iran as a case of the policies, the foreign minister
further stressed that Iran can not enter into talks with the
U.S. under such a situation.
</P>
<P>
Despite strong criticism from the Iranian government, the
U.S. congress recently approved a bill allocating 2.5 million
U.S. dollars for Radio Free Iran which is scheduled to begin
broadcasting in September this year.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. has been pursuing containment policies toward the Gulf
state since the 1979 Islamic revolution in Iran. It broke up
diplomatic relations with Tehran after radical Iranian students
occupied the U.S. Embassy and took staffers hostages in 1980.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian foreign minister also denied the existence of
Japan's mediation between Iran and the U.S., saying that the
recent visit of Japanese state secretary for foreign affairs
Masahiko Komura to Iran had nothing to do with the
Tehran-Washington ties.
</P>
<P>
However, Japanese sources said that Iranian President Mohammad
Khatami asked Komura on Saturday to convey a message to the U.S.,
urging Washington to change its policies to break down the "wall
of mistrust" between the two sides. 
</P>
</TEXT>
