<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Moves to Check Cheating in Pricing Activities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 27 (Xinhua) -- China plans to strictly check
fraudulent pricing activities, a conduct arousing many consumer
complaints, with the state's price law scheduled to go into effect
May 1.
</P>
<P>
According to Wei Dale, an official with the State Development
Planning Commission, the Price Law contains four chapters and 48
articles, which give explicit wording on price cheating.
</P>
<P>
The common fraudulent pricing activities include fictitious
lowering of prices, misunderstanding or vague price indications,
double prices and price discrimination, said the official.
</P>
<P>
He noted that such fraudulent pricing activities have seriously
harmed the interests of consumers and of other traders, causing
chaos in the country's economic life.
</P>
<P>
The price law stipulates a series of penalties for fraudulent
pricing conduct including compensation for the loss suffered by
consumers, fines on illegal traders as much as five times their
illegal gains, stopping business for rectification, or even
revoking their licenses, he said.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, he said, the drafting of the price law is designed to
standardize pricing order in markets and to protect the legitimate
interests of consumers, in a bid to promote fair competition.
</P>
<P>
Price competition is a major means of market competition, but
it should be kept within the scope of relevant laws and
regulations, the official said, or it could undermine regular
market order.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980427.0127 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Seeks to Curb Loss of Farmland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 27 (Xinhua) -- China's top legislative body is
deliberating on amendments to the draft of the Land-Use Law, which
aims to protect the country's farmland resources. China's per
capita acreage of farmland only accounts for 40 percent of the
world's average.
</P>
<P>
The amendments to the draft of the Land-Use Law, which has been
submitted to the second session of the Standing Committee of the
National People's Congress (NPC) for deliberation, clearly points
out that "the state will adopt special policies to protect the
farmland resources, and strictly prevent farmland from
being transferred into non-farmland."
</P>
<P>
The draft says that China also plans to establish a farmland
compensation system in the form of law. "The units that use
farmland for other purposes are entitled to exploit the same
amounts of new farmland," it says.
</P>
<P>
Besides, China is poised to implement a basic farmland
protection system, which means that more than 80 percent of the
country's farmland -- high-yield and arable land for specialties,
new products, and vegetables and scientific research -- is under
strict protection of the government.
</P>
<P>
The draft also stipulates that "no unit or individual is
allowed to leave farmland unused," and those who violate the rules
will be penalized economically or lose their land-use rights.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that China has 130 million hectares of
farmland, with per capita acreage at 0.1 hectare, while the Food
and Agricultural Organization of the United Nations set the global
alarm line at 0.05 hectares per person.
</P>
<P>
Statistics also show that during the last 10 years agricultural
structural adjustment and natural disasters have impaired 4.7
million hectares of farmland, in addition to 1.97 million hectares
of farmland used for non-agricultural purposes.
</P>
<P>
High- and stable-yield farmland, mainly situated in east and
south China, accounts for less than 40 percent of the country's
total farming area, and is also endangered as a result of being
used for other purposes.
</P>
<P>
Senior Chinese officials here have emphasized that China must
formulate and implement the most strict Land-Use Law in the world
to effectively protect the country's limited farmland
resources.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980427.0128 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
