<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Faces Obstacles in Developing Information Technology </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Five major obstacles are
standing in the way of China's progress in information technology,
experts said.
</P>
<P>
One obstacle is the excessive emphasis of human relationships
in the traditional management culture. The tendency leads to a
booming restaurant business since a lot of deals are struck
through heated talks over dinner, while neglecting the use of
"cold computers," this is a view shared by experts attending a
national meeting here.
</P>
<P>
Another problem is caused by ample cheap labor in China, and
this makes the use of a worker much cheaper than the use of a
computer.
</P>
<P>
The traditional way of work is also a hindrance to the
acceptance of modern information technology. While many foreign
companies are abandoning offices following the use of computers,
most Chinese executives like to personally oversee their staff
work.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the fear of losing face also affects the enthusiasm
of Chinese executives, many of whom lack computer knowledge.
</P>
<P>
The last obstacle is the language barrier. Since many Chinese
people do not know English, software should be translated into
English, thus delaying the time for using them. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980427.0130 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Leipzig Exhibition Center Opens Beijing Office </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 27 (Xinhua) -- The International Exhibition
Center of the traditional exhibition city of Leipzig, Germany,
officially opened its Beijing representative office here today.
</P>
<P>
The center began doing business in China last September, with
the German Chamber of Industry and Commerce Beijing office as its
agent.
</P>
<P>
Ulrich Kromer, the center's managing director, announced the
official opening of the Beijing representative office in today's
news conference, and said that 15 Chinese delegations attended
trade fairs in Leipzig last year.
</P>
<P>
China's economy, which remained stable during last year's
financial crisis in Asia, has consolidated the decision of the
Leipzig Exhibition Center to enhance its presence in the Chinese
market, he said.
</P>
<P>
According to Kromer, the cooperation between Chinese businesses
and the center is mainly in the fields of contracts,
transportation, environmental technology and energy.
</P>
<P>
Leipzig, located in central Germany, played host to its first
trade fair in 1895, and has so far established 35 offices
worldwide.
</P>
<P>
The German Chamber of Industry and Commerce also held its
official opening ceremony here this evening. 
</P>
</TEXT>
