<HEADLINE> Tibetan Enterprises Implement Stock System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Five state-owned enterprises in
China's Tibet Autonomous Region have completed reform by adopting
the stock system, with related stock issues raising a total of one
billion yuan (120 million US dollars).
</P>
<P>
Said enterprises, including the Lhasa Beer Brewery and Tibet
Jinzhu, have contributed greatly to the formation and development
of the region's stock market and have piloted enterprise reform,
according to observers.
</P>
<P>
The Lhasa Brewery, which implemented the stock system in 1995,
recorded pretax profits of more than 8 million yuan (964,000 US
dollars) in 1997 alone and witnessed sharp in increases in wage
payments.
</P>
<P>
Eighteen more enterprises are currently applying for stock
reform and local authorities will select four participants to be
experimented with related reform by the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
Tibet plans to have 10 stock companies and one securities firm
by the year 2000, according to local authorities.  
</P>
</TEXT>
