<BODY>
<HEADLINE> OECD Ministerial Meeting Begins in Paris </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, April 27 (Xinhua) -- The 29-member Organization for
Economic Cooperation and Development (OECD) Monday began its
annual ministerial meeting in Paris.
</P>
<P>
The meeting will focus on the financial crisis in Asia, the
economic crisis in Japan, the launch of the European single
currency and the stalked talks on an agreement on multilateral
investment among OECD members, said OECD officials.
</P>
<P>
Although the financial crisis in Asia is said to have only a
limited impact on other parts of the world, the OECD is
particularly worried about the slide and even a recession of
the Japanese economy, the world's second largest.
</P>
<P>
But OECD officials are optimistic that the Japanese economy,
expected to drop by 0.3 percent in its gross domestic product this
year, will recover from the crisis after Tokyo has launched a
massive, 128 billion-dollar economic renewal plan.
</P>
<P>
While the European Union (EU) recently released a report
supporting liberalization of global investment, the recently
resumed negotiations on the Agreement on Multilateral Investment
(AMI) among OECD members is not expected to go far in the near
future.
</P>
<P>
Differences over cultural exceptions, American extra-
territorial laws on trade sanctions, and issues on social and
environmental protection persist between the United States and
European countries.
</P>
<P>
France is stoutly opposed to the AMI and the EU project to
establish a trans-Atlantic free trade zone. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980427.0136 </DOCNO>
