<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fruit Fosters Uygur Centenarians in Xinjiang </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Fresh grapes, Hami melons,
watermelons and other kinds of fruit have fostered more than 500
centenarians in Hotan and Kashi prefectures in northwest China's
Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
A special study conducted by two army hospitals in the region
shows that the amount of hormones in the blood of centenarians
is the same as in those who are 25 to 40 years younger.
</P>
<P>
The study, funded by the World Health Organization (WHO), also
indicates that the male centenarians still have the sex hormone
which makes them fertile.
</P>
<P>
Doctors attributed the centenarians' longevity to their diet of
fresh fruit all year round from which they absorb enough elements
necessary for keeping health and prolonging life.
</P>
<P>
The centenarians inhabit Gobi desert areas neighboring
Taklamakan Desert in the west and southwest parts of Xinjiang.
</P>
<P>
The scarce-population area claims to have the largest number
of centenarians in China. Bama County in south China's Guangxi
Zhuang Autonomous Region, an area that has a population of
260,000, has 79 centenarians.
</P>
<P>
Similar to centenarians in Bama, they often consume maize,
potatoes and beans and had been farming, grazing animals and
hunting to a very old age.
</P>
<P>
Different from Bama centenarians, about one-fifth of the Uygur
centenarians never drink wine or liquor.
</P>
<P>
Bama is located in a mountainous area and most centenarians
often drink low-grade maize or snake wine to relieve rheumatic
pains, cold and encourage blood circulation.
</P>
<P>
About one-fifth of the Uygur centenarians never smoke and most
of them seldom add pungent flavor to their dishes.
</P>
<P>
Like centenarians in other parts of China, 99 percent of the
centenarians are moderate size or thin, and very few have
contracted high-blood presure or cardiovascular disease.
</P>
<P>
Another character of the Uygur centenarians is that they all
have brushed their teeth since childhood and some of them brush
their teeth five times a day; and only half of them lose all of
their teeth.
</P>
<P>
Like centenarians in other places, the clear and fresh air and
harmonious families are also major factors in their longevity.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980427.0138 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lawmakers Call for Forestry Compensation Fund </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Senior Chinese legislators have
called for the establishment of a compensation fund for forestry
ecological benefits to better protect the environment in
state-owned forests.
</P>
<P>
Deliberating the draft amendments to the Forestry Law at the
ongoing second session of the National People's Congress (NPC)
Standing Committee, lawmakers said that it is a good idea to make
such amendment to the law.
</P>
<P>
Lawmaker Wu Shuqing said China is a country in need of forests,
so establishing the fund will be of great significance to protect
shelter forest and special-purpose forests as well as to improve
environmental quality.
</P>
<P>
According to the amendment, the fund will be specifically used
to cultivate, protect and manage shelter forest and special forest
resources which bring about considerable ecological benefits. And
the funds would not be used for other purposes.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, lawmaker Pu Chaozhu said the amendments
should also take into consideration the economic interests of
local residents in addition to the emphasis on overall ecological
and social benefits.
</P>
<P>
Most of the those inhabiting forest areas are ethnic groups who
have to rely on the forests to make a living, Pu said.
</P>
<P>
On the whole, lawmakers said that the Forestry Law, which was
put into effect in 1984, has played a leading role in protecting
and utilizing forest resources. But along with social and economic
development, some of its articles are out of date and need
revision.
</P>
<P>
In panel discussions Sunday, lawmakers also deliberated draft
amendments concerning the transfer of the right of using woods and
forest lands, the requisitioning of forest lands, the issuance of
forest-related certificates in major state-owned forest areas, and
the responsibilities of forestry public security departments.
</P>
<P>
In the discussions, legislators expressed the belief that the
amendments would be passed at the NPC Standing Committee session.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
