<HEADLINE> Nepal, India Agree to Expand Air Routes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Nepal and India have agreed to
expand air routes between them, The Kathmandu Post said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Under an agreement reached last week, both countries will allow
airlines to operate on new routes from towns in the Terai plain in
southern Nepal to major Indian cities, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
The two countries also agreed to redraw the present operational
air routes between them to make air operation more efficient, it
said.
</P>
<P>
Many aviation experts see the opening of new air routes as a
big boost for Nepal's tourism industry, the daily said, adding
that Indian tourists have long been the biggest contributor to
Nepal's tourism, and the new routes are sure to see a jump in the
number of arrivals.
</P>
<P>
Nepal and India renewed a bilateral air services agreement last
June when then Indian Prime Minister I.K. Gujral visited Nepal.
</P>
<P>
The agreement allows private airlines to operate between the
two countries.  
</P>
