<HEADLINE> Afghan Factions Agree on 4-point Agenda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, April 27 (Xinhua) -- The on-going intra-Afghan talks
made important headway as Afghanistan's Islamic Taliban and the
rival Northern Alliance Monday agreed on a four-point agenda
including the formation of the Ulema (religious scholars)
Commission and a ceasefire.
</P>
<P>
Ibrahim Saleh Bakar, assistant secretary general of the
Organization of the Islamic Conference, announced this after the
five-member Taliban team and the nine-member alliance delegation
concluded their four-hour morning session on the second day of the
talks.
</P>
<P>
Bakar said the two sides agreed to consider the formation of
the Ulema Commission, a ceasefire, an exchange of prisoners of war
and the removal of blockade to humanitarian aid.
</P>
<P>
The two sides will continue their talks at 4:00 p.m. (local
time) later in the day, he said.
</P>
<P>
James Ngobi, acting head of the U.N. Special Mission on
Afghanistan, described the atmosphere of the talks as "good" and
said "they have made some progress."
</P>
<P>
Bakar and Ngobi are jointly presiding over the first
face-to-face talks in more than a year between the Taliban and the
alliance which started in the Pakistani Capital Sunday morning.
</P>
</TEXT>
