<DOCNO> XIE19980427.0142 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's GDP Growth Rate To Hit 8.2 Percent, Economists Say (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 27 (Xinhua) -- In spite of a first-quarter
slowdown, the Chinese economy is expected to gain momentum and
generate an 8.2 percent increase for the whole year, according to
an analytical report issued today by veteran economists with the
Chinese Academy of Social Sciences (CASS) and State Statistics
Bureau (SSB).
</P>
<P>
Based on results of analog model research and data analysis,
the report outlines a sound future for the Chinese economy with
the primary industries -- agriculture, fisheries, forestry, animal
husbandry and water conservation -- increasing 3.4 percent in
added value and the secondary and tertiary industries growing by
9.7 percent and 8.3 percent, respectively.
</P>
<P>
The country's GDP growth rate was 8.8 percent last year. The
Chinese government announced that the growth target will be 8
percent this year to maintain a suitable economic momentum and
curb the bubble economic activities while readjusting its
enterprise structure.
</P>
<P>
The biannual analytical survey on the national economy, which
was initiated in 1990 by CASS and SSB, China's top two research
bodies in economics, has been one of the most reliable and
authoritative channels to foretell China's short-term economic
future.
</P>
<P>
Though still among the world's fastest growing economies,
China's is sloping down at "an unexpected speed" as the gross
domestic product (GDP) growth rate dropped to 7.2 percent in the
January-March period.
</P>
<P>
In addition to the Asian financial crisis and inefficient
production structure in Chinese companies, the economic slowdown
was caused by the "remaining influence" of the government's
macro-control policies, which aimed at cooling down the overheated
macroeconomic operation and led to a soft landing in 1996.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980427.0143 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's GDP Growth Rate To Hit 8.2 Percent, Economists Say (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
However, a GDP increase of 8 percent or more could be
guaranteed in terms of both the country's present economic
conditions and growth potential, said economists with CASS and SSB.
</P>
<P>
They said the reshuffling of the central committee of the
Communist Party of China (CPC) at the 15th National CPC Congress
and the new State Council, or China's cabinet, at the last plenum
of the National People's Congress, provides a "stable political
guarantee" for economic development. Both the central and local
governments have made a firm resolution to pick up the economic
growth.
</P>
<P>
As long as the central government's policy on stimulating
economic growth is put into practice in time, China will be able
to solve all the problems hindering high economic growth, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
In order to facilitate a rebound in GDP growth, China has
resorted to a new economic model featuring higher domestic
demand. The new model is expected to take effect in the latter
half of this year, when the central government's investment
programs in fixed assets switch into high gear.
</P>
<P>
For its untapped market potential, the rural area could develop
into a major contributor to the targeted economic growth rate this
year, according to the economists.
</P>
<P>
A fast increase in exports is also possible, as long as China
readjusts the mix of trade partners through exploring more
business opportunities in non-Asian markets little affected by the
financial crisis, they said.
</P>
<P>
According to results of their analytic research, China's
investment in fixed assets will amount to about 2.89 trillion yuan
this year, up 14 percent over the previous year. Retail sales will
reach 2.97 trillion yuan, up 10.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
The exports will be 195.5 billion U.S. dollars, up 7 percent,
achieving a foreign trade surplus of 35.5 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, China expects slightly higher prices this year,
though the inflation rate will be far from reaching an alarm stage.
</P>
<P>
The report estimated that the retail price index will climb by
1.9 percent this year, and the consumer price index by 3.8
percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980427.0144 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Consumer Goods Fair Opens in Shanghai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, April 27 (Xinhua) -- A trade fair featuring new
achievements in German consumer goods production opened today in
Shanghai, China's largest industrial center.
</P>
<P>
German Minister of Economics Guenter Rexrodt cut the ribbon to
mark the opening of the fair.
</P>
<P>
The event marks the first time that Germany has held a
comprehensive consumer goods exhibition in China. The week-long
fair is organized by the Shanghai Municipal Council for the
Promotion of International Trade and the German Ministry of
Economics.
</P>
<P>
More than 200 German manufacturers are exhibiting their most
advanced products, including foodstuffs, beverages, household
electric appliances, textiles, garments, furniture, automobiles,
telecommunications, interior decorations and building
materials. The fair occupies over 17,000 square meters.
</P>
<P>
Germany is one of the major investing nations in China, with
signed contracts valued at over 5.6 billion US dollars. German
companies had established over 1,200 joint ventures throughout
China by the end of 1997.  
</P>
