<HEADLINE> Iranian House Speaker Visits Kuwait </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Iran's parliament Speaker
Ali Akbar Nateq-Nouri arrived here Monday on a three-day visit
aimed at enhancing political, cultural, parliamentary and
economic ties between the two Gulf countries.
</P>
<P>
"Iran believes that exchanging visits might strengthen
brotherly and distinguished ties between our two countries,"
Nouri told reporters upon arrival at the Kuwaiti airport.
</P>
<P>
This is Nouri's second visit to Kuwait in response to an
invitation of his Kuwaiti counterpart Ahmed Al-Sadoun. He paid
his first visit in April 1995 when he signed a memorandum of
understanding with Kuwait including coordination of positions in
conferences of the Inter-Parliamentary Union.
</P>
<P>
During his three-day stay in Kuwait, Nouri will meet Kuwaiti
Amir Sheikh Jabel Al-Ahmed Al-Sabah and members of Kuwaiti
National Assembly.
</P>
<P>
Relations between Kuwait and Iran have been on good terms. Iran
also started last year to make goodwill initiatives towards the
Gulf Cooperation Council states on improving bilateral ties which
had been strained following Tehran's 1979 Islamic revolution.
</P>
<P>
The Gulf Arab states praised the enhancement of relations with
neighboring Iran since moderate President Khatami assumed office
in August 1997.
</P>
<P>
The six-member states of the Gulf Cooperation Council and Iran
have taken several steps towards the upgrading the level of
relations with the two sides believing that building strong ties
is vital for security and stability in the region.
</P>
<P>
In May 1997, Kuwait and Iran signed a bilateral memorandum of
understanding on all aspects of economic and trade cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait and Iran also have been striving to increase their
trade exchanges. Latest statistics showed that the trade
exchanges between Iran and Kuwait stood at nearly 100 million
U.S. dollars in 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
