<HEADLINE> Turkish Army Chief to Visit Russia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Chief of General Staff
Ismail Hakki Karadayi is to visit Moscow from May 18 to 22 to
discuss some tough issues with Russian officials, the Daily News
reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted senior military sources as saying that a
high-level delegation composed of experts on regional problems
and security issues will accompany Karadayi on his visit to Russia.
</P>
<P>
Russia's tolerance of outlawed Kurdish rebels on its territory
will be discussed during the visit. The Kurdish rebels have been
fighting a 14-year-old war in southeastern Turkey against the
Turkish government for an independent Kurdish state.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has accused Russia of training the Kurdish rebels on its
territory, but Russia has denied the charge.
</P>
<P>
The two sides will also discuss Russia's determination to sell
S-300 missiles to Cyprus, which has been divided into the
Greek Cypriot-dominated south and the Turkish Cypriot-controlled
north since 1974 when Turkish troops landed and took over the
northern third of the island in the wake of a pro-Athens coup.
</P>
<P>
The Russian-made S-300 missiles, which Cyprus signed an
agreement with Russia to purchase early last year, are expected to
be deployed on the island later this year. Turkey has threatened
preemptive strikes if the missiles are deployed.
</P>
<P>
"We want to have better, more sincere ties with Russia, but
Moscow should also prove its good intentions toward Ankara," a
senior official said.
</P>
<P>
In addition, Russia's disagreement to the planned Baku-Ceyhan
oil pipeline project is also to be discussed.
</P>
<P>
Turkey supports the oil project that will transport the Caspian
oil through a pipeline from the Azerbaijani capital of Baku and to
the southern Turkish city of Ceyhan.
</P>
<P>
As an energy-starving country, Turkey has been playing an
active role in exploiting the abundant Caspian oil in order to
meet its rapidly increasing energy demands and also earn foreign
exchange through the pipelines that pass through its territory.
</P>
<P>
Russia has expressed its dissatisfaction toward a meeting among
Turkey, Azerbaijan and a number of other related countries for
discussion on the oil project. Russia was not invited to the
meeting held early last month in Istanbul, Turkey. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
