<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Sets up Body to Boost Tourism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 27 (Xinhua) -- The Nigerian government has set up
a national committee to help formulate and implement new policies
toward a take-off of the country's tourism industry.
</P>
<P>
Inaugurating the National Tourism Facilitation Committee in
the capital Abuja over the weekend, Minister of Commerce and
Tourism Emmanuel Udogu said the new organization would advise the
government on the simplification of entry formalities into the
country.
</P>
<P>
The committee is also charged with the responsibility of
ensuring conformity with the provision of healthy and sanitary
regulations of the tourism industry, the Post Express reported
Monday.
</P>
<P>
The committee will equally be responsible for the collection
and dissemination of tourism information and ensure security and
safety of life and property of tourists visiting the country.
</P>
<P>
According to the minister, tourism facilitation committees
will also be established at state and local government levels.
</P>
<P>
Although the government has given priority to the development
of tourism, the industry has remained in dismay without
an appreciable import of tourist arrivals and receipts.
</P>
<P>
The situation resulted from lack of adequate and functional
infrastructural facilities especially good roads, telephone and
electricity, the minister explained.
</P>
<P>
Lack of revenue establishment and the negative behaviors of
some government agencies whose functions are to develop and
promote tourism in the country have contributed to this trend, he
went on.
</P>
<P>
According to Udogu, his ministry has received complaints from
foreign tourists of their frustrating and harrowing experiences
at the nation's entry and exit points.
</P>
<P>
With Nigeria hosting the under 20 World Cup tournament next
year, the way the nation's tourism industry is presented during
the time remain indelible in the minds of those who would come in
as participants or tourists, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
