<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-27 08:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> CIA Spoils Netanyahu's Attempt to Sidestep </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 27 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Central Intelligence
Agency (CIA) has foiled Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu's attempt to send a message on Mideast peace to
President Bill Clinton while sidestepping the Secretary of State.
</P>
<P>
CIA Director George Tenet has recently received the message
from Netanyahu concerning the U.S. role in mediating the Middle
East peace process. But he deemed this as a trick by the Israeli
leader to bypass Madeleine Albright and the State Department.
</P>
<P>
Then, he returned the message to the Israeli prime minister,
Israel's Hebrew daily Haaretz reported in a front-page story on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
By choosing to send messages to the CIA, Netanyahu aimed at
getting them through to Clinton directly without bringing Albright
into the picture, the report said.
</P>
<P>
This was the second message the CIA received from
Netanyahu. The CIA had been puzzled to have received the first
message which was found not sensitive enough for direct delivery
to Clinton.
</P>
<P>
In the message, Netanyahu indicated his willingness to
increase slightly the size of the second redeployment, although in
public he has said Israel will only accept a pullback of 9
percent.
</P>
<P>
The CIA sensed from the wording of the message that Netanyahu
in fact expected Tenet to convey it through his own channels to
Clinton. Instead, the CIA sent a copy of the message to Albright's
office.
</P>
<P>
But soon afterward, Tenet received the second message. This
time Tenet decided to return it to Netanyahu as he concluded that
the Israeli leader was trying to bypass Albright. So the message
was sent back to Netanyahu with a note of explanation, drawn up
jointly by the CIA and the State Department. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
