<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Beverage Industry Growing fast (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAIKOU, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Chinese beverage manufacturers are
currently challenging the dominance of U.S.-based Coca-Cola and
Pepsi in the country.
</P>
<P>
The greatest challenges come from two major Chinese beverage
producers -- the China Coconut Palm Group in the island Province
of Hainan and the Guangdong Jianlibao Group in south China's
Guangdong Province.
</P>
<P>
The two U.S. beverage producers entered the Chinese market with
ease in the early 1980s, gaining the lion's share of the domestic
market and forcing a number of their Chinese counterparts into
bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
Coconut Palm and Jianlibao have since entered the top 20 list
of best-selling beverages in China, along with Coca-Cola and Pepsi.
</P>
<P>
Numerous international consortia have expressed interest in
cooperating with Coconut Palm under favorable conditions. However,
Board Chairman Wang Guangxing declined all offer. "Coconut Palm is
growing without the need for overseas investments or brand name
association, and will continue to do so in the future," said Wang.
</P>
<P>
Coconut Palm's 1997 sales volume was up by 180-fold on the
level for 1986 when the company was founded, and its annual output
has grown from less than 3,000 tons to well over 200,000 tons. The
company has also established more than 2,000 marketing agencies
across the country.
</P>
<P>
The group entered the world market in 1989 and currently
exports products to more than 30 countries and regions, with
annual export sales approaching 50 million yuan. The U.S. Food and
Drug Administration (FDA) granted approval for sales of the
group's natural coconut juice in the United States.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
