<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Is One of Birthplaces For Tulip, Florist Claims </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LANZHOU, April 27 (Xinhua) -- An exhibition of tulips is now
under way in Lanzhou, capital of northwest China's Gansu Province.
</P>
<P>
For most Chinese people, the tulip is a foreign flower from
Europe. The flower has been so beloved by Europeans that at least
three countries from that continent -- the Netherlands, Hungary
and Turkey -- have made it their national flower.
</P>
<P>
"But China is one of the birthplaces for the tulip," said Liang
Shuhai, a florist in northwestern Qinghai Province. Liang is
deputy secretary general of the provincial flower association and
manager of a local park in Xining, the provincial capital of
Qinghai.
</P>
<P>
Chinese experts have discovered 20 wild types of tulip in the
Qinghai-Tibet Plateau, Mount Tianshan in the Xinjiang Uygur
Autonomous Region, and the Qinling Mountain area. It is a proof
that the country is one of the original places for the flower, the
florist said.
</P>
<P>
In the Middle Ages, European crusaders once reached the
northwestern part of China and brought the tulip back to Middle
Asia. Later, in the 17th century, the flower was brought into the
Netherlands and other European areas, according to Liang.
</P>
<P>
"Europeans, especially the Dutch, have been mad at tulip and
they have developed thousands of new types of the flower," the
florist said.
</P>
<P>
China is a late-comer in the cultivation and research of
tulips, but many parts of the country are suitable geographically
and climatically for growing the flower, he said.
</P>
<P>
So far, a number of tulip research and cultivation centers have
been set up in Gansu, Qinghai, Zhejiang and Sichuan provinces.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
