<HEADLINE> Zhejiang Province Trying Harder to Attract Overseas Funds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, April 27 (Xinhua) -- East China's Zhejiang Province
will simplify its procedures for approving investment projects and
will introduce efficient "one window" service so that investors
may complete all necessary procedures in just one place.
</P>
<P>
The province will also establish a province-wide investment
promotion network and will give guidance in directing overseas
investment into such sectors as machine-building, electronics,
chemicals and pharmaceuticals, as well as into upgrading
traditional silk, cotton textile and cement industries.
</P>
<P>
It also intends to attract more overseas funds to speed up
development of agriculture featuring "high quality, high yield and
high efficiency", infrastructure, basic industries and the
high-tech industrial sector, according to information from a
recent provincial meeting on use of overseas investment.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1997, the province had signed contracts with
overseas investors involving a promised use of 25.23 billion
U.S. dollars in overseas funds, but the actual paid-in sum of
overseas funds stood at 10.82 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The province also had approved the establishment of 14,600
overseas-financed businesses, of which, 6,500 had started
operations. The operational overseas-backed businesses contributed
one-fourth of the province's total sales revenue and one-fourth of
exports in 1997, becoming an important part of the province's
economy.
</P>
<P>
The province, situated on the eastern China coast and
economically developed, now has two open coastal cities, 34 open
counties and county-level cities, eight state-level development
zones and a group of provincial-level development zones.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
