<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-27 08:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Envoy Joins Intensive Peace Mediation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 27 (Xinhua) -- European Union (EU) peace
envoy Miguel Moratinos arrived here late Sunday to join the
United States' efforts to break the Israeli-Palestinian deadlock
in Israeli redeployment in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Moratinos held talks with Uzi Arad, diplomatic adviser to
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu, at the Ben-Gurion
Airport upon his arrival before Arad's departure for Washington to
prepare for a scheduled visit by U.S. Vice-President Al Gore to
Israel later this week.
</P>
<P>
They discussed the ongoing diplomatic efforts launched by
U.S. Middle East special envoy Dennis Ross with the aim of
breaking the deadlock over the next stage of Israeli troop
withdrawal in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Ross, who arrived here Saturday with U.S. Assistant Secretary
of State Martin Indyk, has already held two rounds of talks with
Netanyahu and he met in Gaza Sunday night with Palestinian
National Authority (PNA) President Yasser Arafat.
</P>
<P>
To add momentum to the current diplomatic offensive to break
the peace deadlock, Moratinos is to hold talks with Ross, Arafat
and Israeli officials in the next few days.
</P>
<P>
Ross was trying to persuade Israel to accept the U.S.
proposal for a 13.1 percent pullback in the second redeployment,
but there is no sign so far indicating that Netanyahu has
softened his position on rejecting anything more than 9 percent.
</P>
<P>
Chief Palestinian negotiator Saeb Erekat said that the aim of
Ross' mission was mainly "to bring Netanyahu closer to the
U.S. ideas." The PNA has declared its willingness to accept the
U.S. plan, and is waiting for the Israeli response.
</P>
<P>
The main sticking point now seemed to be that while Israel
could agree to increase somewhat the size of the second
redeployment, it intends to abolish the planned third
redeployment. Israel hopes to combine the third redeployment into
the final-status talks.
</P>
<P>
Ross' another mission is to set the stage for the May 4 talks
in London, in which U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright
will hold separate talks with Netanyahu and Arafat in an attempt
to bridge their gap.
</P>
<P>
The London talks were brokered by British Prime Minister
Tony Blair, whose country is holding the rotating EU presidency,
during his visit to the region last week.
</P>
<P>
The prestigious Hebrew daily Haaretz quoted officials
accompanying Ross as saying that the U.S. will decide whether to
table its peace initiative in the London talks at the end of
Ross' mission here.
</P>
<P>
These officials said U.S. President Bill Clinton and Albright
are waiting for the recommendations from Ross, Indyk and Gore
before formulating next steps on advancing the Israeli-Palestinian
talks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
