<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Soil Erosion Worsening along Upper Reaches of Yellow River </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XINING, April 27 (Xinhua) -- The area of soil erosion on the
upper reaches of the 5,464-kilometer Yellow River, China's second
longest after the Yangtze River, has spread to 75,400 square
kilometers, or 51.08 percent of the upper reaches' watershed in
Qinghai Province.
</P>
<P>
A remote sensing survey by the Ministry of Water Resources
shows that soil erosion produces 88 million tons of silt
annually. If this continues, people's life and production will be
seriously affected along the middle and lower reaches, experts
warn.
</P>
<P>
The Yellow River has its source in the Qinghai and runs 1,983
kilometers in the province, involving 2.87 million people and
accounting for nearly 90 percent of the province's rural
population. The watershed is also Qinghai's major grain production
area.
</P>
<P>
However, the area is vulnerable to soil erosion as it lies at
the juncture of the mountainous Loess Plateau and Qinghai-Tibet
Plateau, where torrents and mud-rock flows rush downriver when
rainstorms exceed 10 millimeters.
</P>
<P>
Man-made destruction is also a factor. The area of vegetation
has been decreasing with random reclamation. As a result, the
province's desertification area is thousands of square kilometers
more than two decades ago. And Qinghai suffers 170 million yuan in
direct economic losses from soil erosion alone every year, as well
as 59.9 million kilograms of grain losses. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
