<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaria, Cholera Hit W. Uganda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Malaria and cholera have killed
at least 200 people in western Uganda, The New Vision paper
reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
In the Kisoro District bordering Rwanda, malaria have claimed
140 lives since the disease appeared last month, said Henry
Basaliza Arrali, the Resident District Commissioner.
</P>
<P>
But local leaders put the death number at 180.
</P>
<P>
The district hospital, treating 2,849 cases, was full of
patients. Some patients shared beds in some wards, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
In the district of Bundibugyo bordering the Democratic
Republic of Congo, cholera killed 20 people within three days in
northern Rwebisengo sub-county alone. The total deaths were over
80, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
Bundibugyo is a remote district of this east African country.
</P>
<P>
The southern parts of the district are mountainous while
swamps are dotted here and there in the north.
</P>
<P>
In the El-Nino related rainy season, heavy rains damaged
roads, bridges and created potholes in most of the roads and many
latrines collapsed as a result of the heavy rainfall.
</P>
<P>
The affected areas are lack of clean drinking water, and
unsufficient health facilities also aggravated the crisis.
</P>
<P>
Edward Masiga, the Resident District Commissioner of
Bundibugyo, ordered to close markets across the district to
prevent further spread of the disease and to improve hygiene.
</P>
<P>
Relief aid was dispatched to affected areas, the paper added.
</P>
</TEXT>
