<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Vice-President On Sino-South Korean ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Chinese Vice-President Hu
Jintao said here Monday that China will push forward its economic
and trade cooperation with South Korea.
</P>
<P>
Delivering a speech at a banquet hosted by South Korean
business leaders, Hu said that there are many favorable conditions
for China and South Korea to expand their cooperation since they
are close and friendly neighbors sharing similar culture and
tradition with good political relations and complementary
economies.
</P>
<P>
The industrial and commercial circles of the two nations, in
line with the spirit of mutual benefit, should enlarge exchange
and cooperation in economy and trade by exploring various avenues
and giving free rein to their advantages.
</P>
<P>
The economic and trade ties could be further developed so long
as the two countries make joint efforts, said Hu, who arrived here
Sunday for a five-day official visit.
</P>
<P>
The trade volume between China and South Korea rose to 24
billion U.S. dollars in 1997 from the 4.44 billion dollars in 1991.
</P>
<P>
China and South Korea established diplomatic relations in 1992.
</P>
<P>
Kim Sang Ha, president of the Korea Chamber of Commerce and
Industry, said at the banquet that China is now the third largest
trade partner of South Korea while South Korea has become China's
fourth largest trade partner.
</P>
<P>
China's 8 percent economic growth and its low inflation rate
have served as a strong support to its neighbors who are striving
for economic recovery, he said, adding that China's economic
potentials will help promote South Korean-Chinese economic
cooperation and contribute greatly to the stability and growth of
the economies in Asia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
