<HEADLINE> Buses Provide Access to Remote Tibetan Prefecture </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Ali Prefecture, a remote region in
northwestern Tibet Autonomous Region with abundant tourism
resources and cultural relics, used to have few visitors due to
geographical, climate and transportation conditions.
</P>
<P>
Since 1996, however, things have changed greatly when the first
three regular public buses then began operating between Shiquanhe,
the prefectural seat of government, and Lhasa, the regional
capital.
</P>
<P>
More than 5,000 people from inland areas and abroad
have since journeyed to Ali on buses specially designed
and manufactured by a Chongqing bus manufacturing plant.
</P>
<P>
The Shiquanhe-Lhasa bus route will soon be supplemented by a
route from Shiquanhe to Yecheng in the Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous
Region to the north, according to Li Xihui, director of the Ali
Communications Bureau. 
</P>
</TEXT>
