<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Key Project on China's Yellow River </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZHENGZHOU, April 27 (Xinhua) -- The Xiaolangdi water control
project on the Yellow River will be able to stop the kind of
flooding that occurs every 100 years, this year, Chinese experts
say.
</P>
<P>
The project will allow the area to withstand flood waters below
182 meters this year. The flood season usually comes in July.
</P>
<P>
The two cofferdams have risen to the height of 185 meters, with
the remaining seven meters to be completed by the end of this
month.
</P>
<P>
The damming began last October. Since then, more than 19
million cubic meters of earth and stone have been put into the
dam, or 37 percent of the total amount needed.
</P>
<P>
Work on the underground power room, which measures 251 m. high
by 61 m., has been completed and workers are pouring the concrete
for the generator area.
</P>
<P>
This is the second largest water control project in China,
after the Three Gorges. It now can stop the kind of flooding that
occurs every 60 years but will be able to stop the kind that
occurs every 1,000 years when it is completed in 2001.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
