<HEADLINE> NZ National Party Enjoys Growing Support </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Support for the New Zealand
National Party continued to grow since the party changed its
leadership late last year, the latest opinion poll shows.
</P>
<P>
The party now enjoys 46 percent of the support rating, up 3
percent since the last poll, Television New Zealand reported
Monday night.
</P>
<P>
The popularity of the major opposition party, the Labor Party,
sank to 38 percent, the lowest point in 11 months.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, 33 percent of those polled rated the present Prime
Minister Jenny Shipley as the most preferred prime minister, while
only 21 percent gave the credit to Labor leader Helen Clark, who
once enjoyed the highest rating as the preferred prime minister.
</P>
<P>
If translated into seats in the parliament, the National Party
would have 58 MPs. And the ACT party, which shares many policies
with the National Party, would win 6 seats.
</P>
<P>
The two parties would then have 64 MPs combined, enough to form
a majority government and is even more than the majority the
present coalition government has. 
</P>
</TEXT>
