<DOCNO> XIE19980427.0178 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Trade Official Predicts Moderate Export Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 27 (Xinhua) -- The 1998 growth rate for China's
export will remain at or above 10 percent this year, according to
a senior Chinese trade official.
</P>
<P>
The official with the Ministry of Foreign Trade and Economic
Cooperation noted that the country's exports to Japan declined by
1.7 percent in the first quarter when compared to the same 1997
period, its exports to the Republic of Korea fell by 22
percent and to Indonesia by 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
However, sharp increases were recorded in exports to North
America, Europe, Latin America and various other Asian countries,
according to Li Jian, deputy director of the the ministry's China
Trade Research Department.
</P>
<P>
The latter export increases offset the negative influences of
the financial crisis in Southeast Asia, said Li.
</P>
<P>
China has introduced a technology-intensive processing system
with funds imported from abroad in recent years. The country
enjoys ample domestic supplies and a stable market, and many
Chinese enterprises have enhanced their awareness of international
competition. Li cited the aforementioned areas as favorable
factors for increasing exports.
</P>
<P>
Li addressed China's import situation for this year by noting
that many economists have adopted a positive approach to the
growth of imports. However, the slowdown in investments during the
first quarter resulted in only a slight increase in imports.
</P>
<P>
The promulgation of a series of government policies on
investment will spark a rebound in the growth rate for imports
during the latter half of the year, said Li.
</P>
<P>
Li predicted that China's import growth rate will reach 10
percent, with a favorable balance of some 40 billion U.S. dollars
for the year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
