<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-27 07:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kuwait Seeks Non-Oil Sources of Revenue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, April 27 (Xinhua) -- The Kuwaiti government is
considering a number of economic measures searching for new
sources of income in response to the fall of oil prices, local
newspapers reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The government wants to "diversify revenue (sources), reduce
public expenditures and improve the management of public funds in
response to fall in oil prices," Kuwaiti Deputy Prime Minister and
Minister of State for Cabinet Affairs Nasser Abdallah Al-Roudhan
was quoted as saying after a weekly cabinet meeting Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
The minister said the cabinet discussed a memorandum by the
Ministry of Finance that deals with the impact of declining oil
prices on the treasury.
</P>
<P>
The memo "includes 27 measures that should be implemented to
cut public spending and reduce challenges facing the budget
including its deficit," he added.
</P>
<P>
The economic committee of the cabinet is scheduled to meet
Wednesday and will study the memo and report back to the cabinet.
</P>
<P>
The nine-year low oil prices in the world market since the
start of this year has a very negative impact on the country's
economy.
</P>
<P>
Kuwaiti Oil Minister Sheikh Saud Nasser Al-Sabah warned Sunday
that Kuwait could face an "economic catastrophe" if Kuwaiti
crudes remained at 10.5 U.S. dollars a barrel.
</P>
<P>
The budget of 1998-99 fiscal year (July 1 to June 30), which is
based on an oil price of 12 U.S. dollars a barrel, was approved in
mid-April. It forecasts a deficit of 5.6 billion dollars, the
highest deficit since the 1991 Gulf War and 41 percent higher than
the 1997-98 budget deficit.
</P>
<P>
The Cabinet meeting was devoted to an assessment of the
country's financial and economic situation, Al-Roudhan said,
adding that the proposed measures seek to improve revenues and
rationalize spending.
</P>
<P>
The measures also aim to improve the efficiency of managing of
public funds especially by stopping unnecessary spending, he added.
</P>
<P>
He said the cabinet "blessed the proposals in the memo and
asked the economic committee to suggest methods for
implementation." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
