<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing Improves Medical Emergency Aid Network </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Beijing has established a
comprehensive emergency medical assistance network to serve local
residents, according to health department officials.
</P>
<P>
The center, the most advanced emergency facility of its kind in
China, was jointly funded by the Chinese and Italian
governments. The 24-hour center operates 80 ambulances and is
equipped with state-of-the-art telecommunications facilities.
</P>
<P>
The Beijing Emergency Center, which offers the 120 Emergency
line, has received more than 430,000 assistance calls over the
past decade. The organization has provided timely services for
over 50,000 critically ill people.
</P>
<P>
The center's communications network is linked directly to the
the airport, and transportation, railway and subway management
departments.
</P>
<P>
Early this year, medical personnel responded to an accident on
the Beijing-Tianjin-Tangshan Expressway withing 40 minutes of the
report, according to officials. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980427.0181 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hu Jintao On China's Economic Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Chinese Vice-President Hu
Jintao said Monday that an economically developed and prosperous
world needs China while China could not grow and flourish without
the world.
</P>
<P>
Hu made this remark when addressing South Korean business
leaders here on Monday morning.
</P>
<P>
In face of the tremendous economic pressure and challenges
produced by the financial crisis in some Asian nations, China has
announced in a responsible manner that it will not devalue its
currency and has provided funds to those countries within its
ability.
</P>
<P>
It is not easy for China, which is still a developing country,
to do so, but China's commitment is serious and based on facts, Hu
said.
</P>
<P>
Although affected by the financial turmoil late last year,
China still reached an economic growth rate of 8.8 percent and an
inflation rate of 0.8 percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The good momentum of "high growth and low inflation" in economy
has laid a solid foundation for the stability of China's currency
exchange rate, Hu said.
</P>
<P>
The steady growth of China's foreign currency reserves, the
rational structure of its foreign debt, most of which are
long-term ones, and the low cost of labor force, which makes
China's export still competitive, have all made it possible to
maintain the value of the Renminbi (China's currency), Hu noted.
</P>
<P>
China is pleased to see that the sign of economic recovery has
emerged in some crisis-affected Asian nations and China believes
that the crisis will be overcome soon with the efforts of those
countries as well as the international community, Hu said.
</P>
<P>
Hu voiced the belief that Asia will return to the world
economic stage with its high speed of economic development in the
next century.
</P>
<P>
China has made a breakthrough in the past five years in
establishing a system of socialist market-oriented economy, Hu
said, adding that a structure for opening wider to the outside
world has taken shape.
</P>
<P>
Hu described China's main targets of economic development in
1998 as achieving an 8 percent economic growth rate, keeping
inflation rate below 3 percent and safeguarding the value of its
currency.
</P>
<P>
To reach the targets will not only serve China's stability and
development, but also is conducive to the stability and prosperity
in Asia, said Hu.
</P>
<P>
To this end, China has taken a series of steps, including the
unshakable implementation of reforms, especially the further
reform of state-run enterprises, financial system and government
structure, said the Chinese vice-president.
</P>
<P>
South Korea is the second leg of Hu's East Asia tour, which has
taken him to Japan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
