<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980427.0182 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenyan Firms in Move to Fight Music Piracy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 27 (Xinhua) -- An initiative by a group of
Kenyan music companies may lead to the introduction of a more
effective system of protecting music dealers from piracy and
illegal imports.
</P>
<P>
The proposed measure, known as the Banderole system, is being
formulated by major record companies and the Value Added Tax
department and is expected to take effect before the end of this
year, the East African weekly reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
It requires music companies to submit information to all their
labels and franchises to the VAT department and carry a security
band around cassettes or CDs for identification.
</P>
<P>
The bands will be purchased from the VAT department at an
equivalent of 17 percent of the retail price of the CDs and
cassettes. This will effectively be an advance payment of VAT and
is also intended to ensure a more efficient collection of the
tax.
</P>
<P>
According to the International Federation of Producers of
Phonograms and Videograms, piracy controls at least 80 percent of
the Kenyan music market.
</P>
<P>
In February, supported by major international record
companies, Kenyan licenses of overseas producers took measures to
stop parallel importation of music products.
</P>
<P>
The information submitted to the VAT department under the
Banderole system will also be useful in resolving industry
disputes over rights ownership.
</P>
<P>
However, some producers feel that this added cost is an extra
financial burden on the record companies, which are suffering
from the effects of declining sales. But others see it as a
necessary cost in containing piracy.
</P>
<P>
AI Record's director John Andrews and Managing Director of
Music World Kenya Ltd John Njagi said the Banderole system may
not directly relate to copyright infringement but it would
deprive pirates of the price advantage which has fanned the
counterfeit trade in Kenya.
</P>
<P>
Under the new system, every music cassette, video or compact
disc will be required to have a VAT band.
</P>
<P>
The price of pirate audio cassettes and CDs is 100 Kenyan
Shillings (1.66 U.S. Dollars) and 700 Shillings (11.66 Dollars)
respectively, while legitimate cassettes retail at 200 Shillings
(3.33 Dollars) for cassettes and 1,300 (21.66 Dollars) for CDs.
</P>
<P>
The price of pirate music videos is 300 Shillings (five
Dollars), compared to 800 Shillings (13.33 Dollars) a piece for
legitimate ones.
</P>
<P>
The 17 percent value added tax will be charged uniformly on
all music carriers based on the price of legitimate cassettes and
compact discs. This is expected to force pirates to increase
their retail prices, but will not affect the price of legitimate
products, which are already VAT inclusive.
</P>
<P>
Njagi, however, said the new system needs governmental
commitment to succeed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980427.0183 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-27 07:57 </DATE_TIME>
