<HEADLINE> Shenzhen to Hold Land Auctions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENZHEN, April 27 (Xinhua) -- The Shenzhen Special Economic
Zone will auction two lots, one residential and the other
commercial, covering a total of 50,818 sq.m. on May 20.
</P>
<P>
The auction will be city's first land auction in over five
years.
</P>
<P>
The two pieces of property are part of eight lots covering
229,900 square meters the city plans to auction by the end of this
year.
</P>
<P>
Shenzhen, a special economic zone, and neighboring Hong Kong
pioneered the sale of land-use rights on December 1, 1987. Five
lots covering a total of 55,319 sq.m. were sold by May 1993.
</P>
<P>
Land sale came to an abrupt halt in the latter part of 1993
when China's property market entered a period of
readjustment. Shenzhen responded by accelerating legislation and
improving the management of real estate deals.
</P>
<P>
Shenzhen adopted the Rules Governing Bids and Auctions of
Land-Use Rights on February 6 this year. The rules stipulate that
bidding and auction methods should be adopted for land sales.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that most of Shenzhen's total land supply of
10.4 million sq.m. is supplied through signing of agreement
between the government and user. 
</P>
</TEXT>
