<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Southwestern Province Protects Religious Activities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Southwest China's Yunnan Province
has made efforts to protect religious activities. So far, more
than 3,000 temples, lamaseries and churches have been opened for
local religious believers.
</P>
<P>
Yunnan is a multi-cultural province with multiple religions,
with 25 ethnic groups whose members mostly are followers of
Buddhism, Islam, Christianity and Catholicism.
</P>
<P>
Most local religious sites were damaged during the "Cultural
Revolution" (1966-1976). Since 1978, efforts have been made by
local governments at all levels to resume once-banned religious
activities, and to rebuild and reopen places of worship.
</P>
<P>
Currently, the province has more than 1,700 Bali Buddhist
temples, 25 Tibetan lamaseries, 290 Chinese Buddhist temples, 717
Islamic churches, 1,400 Christian churches and 30 Catholic
churches.
</P>
<P>
There are more than 4,100 Islamic clergymen and 1,000 Christian
missionaries in the province. Local Buddhist temples have also
sent many of their clergymen to study in Tibet or other parts of
the country.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, local religious bodies have published hundreds of
thousands of religious books in six major ethnic languages and
Arabic. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
