<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Huge Fund Planned for Human Genome Research </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 27 (Xinhua) -- China will spend 7 million yuan
(843,000 U.S. dollars) launching a human genome project in the
next four years to ensure that the country will be competitive in
the field of genetics in the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
The funding for the project, "Studies on Structure and Function
of the Chinese Human Genome," is the biggest among 16 major
research projects during the 1996-2000 period sponsored by the
National Natural Science Fund Committee (NNSFC).
</P>
<P>
Part of the funding will be used to support the collection
of genes of various Chinese ethnic groups and build a bank of
cells.
</P>
<P>
The genetic relations between different ethnic groups,
such as the genetic difference between people in south and north
China, and the origination and immigration of modern Chinese will
be studied under the project.
</P>
<P>
Money will also be spent on studies of genes related to the
major traits of Chinese people and some major genetic diseases.
</P>
<P>
Experts said the project is expected to help create and develop
new theories and techniques of the functional genome science in
China, which has 22 percent of the world's population and 56
ethnic groups.
</P>
<P>
The Human Genome Project (HGP), the largest biological and
medical research project in the world, aims to interpret the
genetic codes of humans and help prevent and treat more than 6,000
genetic diseases. The United States began HGP research in 1990,
and planned to invest 3 billion U.S. dollars within 15 years.
</P>
<P>
In 1994, NNSFC started the first human genome project in China,
"Studies on Several Gene Loci Structure of the Chinese Human
Genome," with a total funding of 3.6 million yuan (450,000 US
dollars). It has involved 16 research institutes across the
country and produced significant results.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, the State Science and Technology Commission launched
another project, "Studies on Genes Related to Major Diseases," and
planned to spend 13 million yuan building an HGP center in Beijing
and 20 million yuan for a center in Shanghai. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
