<DOCNO> XIE19980427.0199 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Private Businesses Make Big Profits From Export </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Liu Deqing has a very small shop
in the Yabaolu Garment Market, downtown Beijing, too small to
accommodate five-to-six people in addition to rows of garments
hung on the walls.
</P>
<P>
However, this handicap doesn't prevent him from doing big
businesses. With just a telephone call, he can send thousands of
kilograms of garments by air to Moscow.
</P>
<P>
The 400-meter-long Yabaolu Road, located near Beijing's embassy
compound, has more than 2,000 stalls along its two sides,
involving more than 4,000 peddlers like Liu.
</P>
<P>
These peddlers sell Chinese-made garments and toys. The road
has become the biggest outdoor market in the Chinese capital
involved in garment exports.
</P>
<P>
At present, the market's export volume stands at 1 billion
U.S. dollars, or 40 percent of Beijing's annual total.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, seven aircrafts carried more than 300 tons of garments
daily released from the Yabaolu Road to eastern European countries.
</P>
<P>
However, businesses here seem to keep expanding.
</P>
<P>
Liu, who has made a profit of 1 million yuan in the last 10
years, has asked his younger sister to work with him, providing
her with a mobile phone on the first day she worked. 
</P>
</TEXT>
