<DOCNO> XIE19980427.0200 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Urban Population Outnumbers Rural in China's Agro-Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARBIN, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Northeast China's Heilongjiang
Province has claimed to be the country's first big agro-province
where urban residents have outnumbered rural population.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that, at the end of 1997, the province had an
urban population of 20.22 million and rural of 17.29 million.
</P>
<P>
The rural population doubled that of the urban one in 1977. In
the last 20 years, the number of towns increased from 102 to 466
and small cities from two to 20.
</P>
<P>
Wu Hengju, associate researcher of the China Society for Study
of Urban Economy, believes the reform and opening-up drive has
given rise to the establishment of small cities and towns.
</P>
<P>
The agricultural province has not encouraged farmers to seek
jobs in big cities, instead focusing on the development of small
cities and towns.
</P>
<P>
One example of this trend is Ma Dequan, 32, who was granted
residence in Zhoujia Town by a local public security agency last
month after he managed a store and built a house in the town near
his village in the eastern part of Heilongjiang.
</P>
<P>
He is among millions of farmers in the province who have given
up their "responsibility plots" and resettled in towns or small
cities. Most of them are engaged in commerce and the service
sector.
</P>
<P>
With the practice of a household contract responsibility system
since the 1980s, Heilongjiang's annual grain output has risen from
15 billion kilograms to 30 billion, and it ranks first in selling
commodity crops among China's provinces and autonomous regions.
</P>
<P>
Heilongjiang also has the biggest number of large- and
medium-size tractors among other provinces.
</P>
<P>
Agronomists believe that the large amount of surplus farm
produce and surplus laborers brought out by agro-mechanization are
the basic conditions for the rapid growth of urbanization.
</P>
<P>
The urbanization drive also encouraged economic growth in new
cities. The average agricultural and industrial growth rate in
Zhaodong and Anda, two cities growing out of counties, are 8
percent higher than that of other cities in the region.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980427.0201 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Purified Water Selling Well in Shanghai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Purified water will become the
most popular drink in the Shanghai market this year, according to
a recent market survey.
</P>
<P>
Sales of purified water in Shanghai have increased at an annual
rate of 20 percent in the last few years.
</P>
<P>
Many institutions and enterprises have installed drinking water
dispensers in offices and factories. An increasing number of urban
residents said they prefer purified water to boiled water.
</P>
<P>
Purified water is expected to make up 40 percent of total sales
in the soft drink market this summer. Sales of colorless carbonic
drinks will account for a quarter of the local market, the survey
said.
</P>
<P>
Mineral water is expected to take a market share of 20 percent;
fruit or vegetable juice, 10 percent; and milk products, 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
This reflects a trend that more residents favor natural
products and indicates increased competition in the soft drink
market, said a municipal official.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
