<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-27 07:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. NGOs Call for Establishment of Palestinian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 27 (Xinhua) -- The Non-governmental Organizations
(NGOs) have called for the full implementation of the United
Nations resolution on setting up an independent Palestinian state
in May 1999, the Middle East News Agency reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The call was made in a final statement issued at the end of a
two-day U.N. International NGOs Conference on the Question of
Palestine concluded in Cairo Sunday. The gathering was the first
NGOs meeting convened in the Middle East region.
</P>
<P>
"We affirm that the question of Palestine is, fundamentally,
about the struggle for land, and the fulfillment of the
inalienable Palestinian right to a state with Jerusalem as its
capital," said the final statement.
</P>
<P>
The declaration of principles, signed by the Palestinians and
Israelis in September 1993, and most recently reaffirmed in
U.N. General Assembly, raised hope for stability and peace in the
region, the statement.
</P>
<P>
The statement said it is clear that the policies of the present
Israeli government have undermined any confidence and trust in the
current peace process.
</P>
<P>
The NGOs noted that the U.N. and the international community
have a "continuing and unfulfilled responsibility" for a just
resolution of the question of Palestine.
</P>
<P>
The two-day gathering included workshops on the way of
assuaging the economic and social suffering of the Palestinian
people under the Israeli policy.
</P>
<P>
The NGOs reiterated their commitment to a just and lasting
peace based on self-determination for the Palestinian people,
calling for international protection of the Palestinians' rights
prior to the full implementation of the U.N. resolution.
</P>
<P>
In support of this goal, the NGOs redeclared their recognition
of the state of Palestine.
</P>
<P>
"We look to 1999 as the year of the state of Palestine and will
work with our constituencies and the public to prepare them for
the declaration of the independent state by the Palestinian
Authority," the statement added.
</P>
<P>
The participants urged additional NGO events to be held in the
region next year, particularly in Palestine.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian-Israeli talks were stalled a year ago when
Israel began construction of the Jewish housing project on Har
Homa in East Jerusalem, which the Palestinians want as the capital
of their would-be state.
</P>
<P>
Frustrated over the lack of progress in the peace process,
Palestinian National Authority President Yasser Arafat and
Palestinian officials have recently repeated their determination
to declare an independent Palestinian state in 1999, regardless of
achieving a peace treaty with Israel or not. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
