<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Support Rate for Hashimoto Drops to Record-Low </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Public support rate for Japanese
cabinet, led by Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto, has dropped to
28 percent, the lowest since it was set up in January 1996, a leading
Japanese newspaper poll showed.
</P>
<P>
The rate was eight percentage points lower than a previous poll
in March and the second lowest following the 26 percent approval
rating posted by former Prime Minister Kiichi Miyazawa's cabinet
in April 1993, according to the Asahi Shimbun newspaper poll.
</P>
<P>
Fifty-one percent of respondents disapproved of the Hashimoto's
cabinet, up four percentage points from the March survey and
exceeding 50 percent for the first time since its establishment.
</P>
<P>
Those who supported Hashimoto's resignation and the set-up of a new
cabinet totaled 57 percent, while only 22 percent favored the
cabinet's continuing, the poll showed.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, 43 percent said they disapproved of the government's
latest 16 trillion yen (about 123.1 billion U.S. dollars) economic
stimulus package to boost the stagnant economy, while 36 percent
said they supported the measures, the poll said.
</P>
<P>
Japan's economic situation has been worsening despite a series
of pump-priming measures were announced by the government.
</P>
<P>
Of the 1,558 randomly selected voters, 1,068 responded to the
telephone survey conducted by the paper on Saturday and Sunday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
