<HEADLINE> Chinese Naval Ships Start Visit to New Zealand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AUCKLAND, New Zealand, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Two Chinese naval
ships arrived here Monday morning to begin a four-day visit to New
Zealand.
</P>
<P>
The two vessels, the guided-missile destroyer "Qiangdao" and
the training ship "Shichang", were on a three-nation South
Pacific visit which also includes Australia and the Philippines.
</P>
<P>
While sailing into the Queens Wharf here, "Qiangdao" fired a
21-gun salute to pay tribute to the New Zealand national flag.
The New Zealand Royal Navy did the same to pay tribute to the
Chinese National flag.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a welcome ceremony at the wharf, New Zealand
Maritime Commander Commodore Peter McCharfei said this is the
first time that a Chinese naval fleet has arrived in New Zealand
for a visit.
</P>
<P>
The visit itself underlines the growing friendship between New
Zealand and China, he stated, adding that he was very much
impressed by "Qiangdao" when he saw her entering the harbor.
</P>
<P>
Commissioned in 1996 and equipped with guided missiles and
helicopters, the 4,800-ton "Qiangdao" is one of the most advanced
vessels of the Chinese navy.
</P>
<P>
In his speech, leader of the visiting fleet Rear Admiral Han
Fangrun said the visit is aimed to increase the understanding,
exchanges and friendship between the militaries of China and New
Zealand, and to enable the militaries of the two countries to
learn from each other.
</P>
<P>
Waving the flags of China and New Zealand, hundreds of New
Zealand Chinese were also among those at the wharf to greet the
Chinese fleet. They toured the ships shortly after the vessels
docked at the wharf.  
</P>
</TEXT>
