<HEADLINE> Vietnamese Auto Market in Tough Times </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Slack demand for automobiles has
caused considerable losses to 14 foreign-invested manufactures in
Vietnam, auto investors said Monday.
</P>
<P>
In the first three months of this year, only 600 automobiles
from companies like Toyota, Daihatsu and Mazda have hit the
streets, the investors were quoted by the Vietnam News as saying.
</P>
<P>
Economists said that current prices for domestically-assembled
cars remain rather high compared with the average Vietnamese
income. Car makers failed to reduce prices to expand market demand.
</P>
<P>
At present, a Kia Pride sells for 13,000 U.S. dollars, a Daewoo
Cielo for 19,000 dollars, a Mazda 323 for 26,000 dollars and a
Toyota Corolla for 24,000 dollars.
</P>
<P>
Industry analysts said that Vietnam's auto sector is still in
its infancy. As a result, industrial development over the past few
years has not met the expectations of auto makers.
</P>
<P>
Only 6,000 vehicles were sold on Vietnam's auto market last
year, much lower than the 1996's figure. 
</P>
</TEXT>
