<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dhaka Reduces Import Tariff to Minimum Level: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh has reduced the import
tariff to a minimum level, Commerce and Industries Minister Tofael
Ahmed said.
</P>
<P>
Although it is one of the least developed countries, Bangladesh
has withdrawn not-tariff barriers and quantitative restrictions on
import, the minister told Secretary General Naeem U Hasan of the
South Asian Association for Regional Cooperation (SAARC) Sunday,
the Independent daily reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Bigger SAARC economies like India and Pakistan, however, are
not reciprocating the country's liberalization process, he said.
</P>
<P>
India informed Bangladesh that it had reduced import tariff on
more than 200 items and withdrawn restrictions on many items, but
Bangladesh has a very little scope to export those items, he
noted.
</P>
<P>
Hasan, who was here to attend the first SAARC information
ministers' meeting ended Sunday, requested the minister to discuss
the issues in the coming SAARC commerce ministers' meeting to be
held in Islamabad, Pakistan, on Wednesday and Thursday.
</P>
<P>
SAARC countries have bright prospect to prosper through
joint-venture investment projects, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
