<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hainan Protects Endangered Species </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAIKOU, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Hainan, China's southernmost
island province, has protected endangered flora and fauna since
gaining provincial status in 1988 by expanding the coverage of
nature reserves.
</P>
<P>
The number of such reserves has grown from 52 to 78 over
the past 10 years, with the total coverage of 2.66 million
ha. including maritime reserves of 2.51 million hectares.
</P>
<P>
The province's 68 land and 10 sea reserves have played a major
role in protecting endangered animals and plants.
</P>
<P>
The number of Hainan's deer herd has grown from 26 to over 600,
and the monkey population grew from 30 to over 1,800.
</P>
<P>
The province's forest coverage has also expanded rapidly, with
the forest coverage in the Wuzhishan Mountainous area climbing
from 66 percent to near 90 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
