<HEADLINE> China, S. Korea to Seek Closer Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Chinese Vice-President Hu
Jintao Monday said China attaches great importance to the
development of good relations between China and South Korea.
</P>
<P>
During his meeting with South Korean Acting Prime Minister Kim
Jong-pil, Hu said that the development of Sino-South Korean ties
not only conforms to the fundamental interests of the two peoples,
but also serve peace, stability and development on the Korean
Peninsula.
</P>
<P>
China would like to make joint efforts with South Korea to push
the long-term, stable and good-neighborly Sino-South Korean
relations into the 21st century, said Hu, who arrived here Sunday
for a five-day official visit.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese vice-president said China appreciates the
commitment made by the South Korean new government to abide by the
"one China" principle, which was set in the agreement signed when
China and South Korea established diplomatic relations in 1992.
</P>
<P>
Hu, also a member of the Political Bureau Standing Committee of
the Central Committee of the Communist Party of China (CPC),
appreciated Kim's contribution to promoting mutual understanding
and friendship between the CPC and the South Korean United Liberal
Democrats as well as to enhancing Sino-South Korean ties.
</P>
<P>
Kim Jong-pil said Hu's current visit will further strengthen
the friendly and cooperative links between South Korea and China.
</P>
<P>
Echoing Hu's evaluation of bilateral ties, Kim added that his
country will continue to support and cooperate with China, and
expressed the hope that the two countries will continue to help
each other.
</P>
<P>
The acting prime minister said that his nation is willing to
seek collaboration with China in the fields of fisheries, tourism
and peaceful use of nuclear energy, while boosting youth exchanges
between the two countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
