<BODY>
<HEADLINE> University Students May Choose Their Own Teachers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Students in a university in
northwest China's Shaanxi Province now are allowed to select their
own teachers instead of having classes totally arranged by the
school, according to today's Guangming Daily.
</P>
<P>
This change is one of the educational reforms in the Northwest
China Institute of Political Science and Law, which announces a
list of teachers and their resumes at the beginning of each term
to help students make their selections.
</P>
<P>
"I have decided on some lecturers in accordance with my
preferences and study habits," said Ning Guodong, a freshman in
the Department of Law. In China, class schedules used to be
arranged by schools and teachers designated by departments.
</P>
<P>
Professor Ge Hongyi, who taught jurisprudence, attracted more
than 250 students to his class last term, compared sharply with
another professor who only had 19 applicants.
</P>
<P>
According to the institute, if a teacher has less than 30
applicants, his classes will be canceled.
</P>
<P>
"I felt worried," said Professor Xu Junlun, who attracted 33
applicants last year. He later made efforts to improve his
teaching methods, enrich study contents and organize class
discussions.
</P>
<P>
Guo Jie, a director of the institute, said the reform has been
widely accelerated by students and the quality of teaching
improved when competitiveness was introduced among teachers.
</P>
</TEXT>
