<HEADLINE> Kenya Arrests Leading Ugandan Rebel in Bomb Probe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Kenya police last week arrested
a leading Ugandan dissident in connection with a series of bomb
explosions which rocked Kampala early this month.
</P>
<P>
Although top police officials were non-committal on the number
of Ugandan dissidents rounded up in the mid-week operation,
sources said the former National Resistance Movement captain was
being held at the Kilimani police station in Nairobi, the East
African weekly reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Police spokesman Peter Kimanthi told the East African that he
required more time to establish the facts of the matter.
</P>
<P>
Three other Ugandans locked up at central police station were
being held in connection with immigration inquiries.
</P>
<P>
Kampala was said to have sought Nairobi's assistance in
arresting dissidents following bombing incidents in the Ugandan
capital on April 4, in which five people died. Some of the
suspects were said to have fled to Kenya.
</P>
<P>
One of the dissidents sought by Kenyan police was identified
as a former chemistry lecturer at Makerere University who has
been a political refugee in Kenya since Ugandan President Yoweri
Museveni took over power.
</P>
<P>
The bomb blasts came 10 days after U.S. President Bill Clinton
left Kampala during his landmark six-nation African tour. Ugandan
police said at the time that home-made bombs were assembled from
locally available materials such as water pipes, crop chemicals
and dry cells.
</P>
<P>
The total number of suspects so far arrested by Ugandan police
stands at eight. 
</P>
