<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ancient Tombs Discovered in North China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HOHHOT, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Some 20 ancient tombs dating back
over 900 years and a large cache of cultural relics were recently
discovered in north China's Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
Archeologists believed the tombs date to the Western Xia
(1038-1227) period when the region was inhabited by Dangxiang, an
ancient Chinese ethnic group in northwest China.
</P>
<P>
The tombs, located in southern Inner Mongolia, consist of paved
pathways, gates and coffin chambers. The discovery included brick
gates, and murals depicting people, flowers and curtains
decorating the interior walls of tombs.
</P>
<P>
More than 100 relics, including pottery, porcelain and
stone implements, were also unearthed.
</P>
<P>
Archeologists noted that the Western Xia period in northwest
China lasted more than 200 years, with indigenous people
developing their own language and culture. However, the rarity of
historical documents has led to continuing mystery concerning the
period, and the new finds are expected to greatly benefit research
related to the ancient kingdom. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980427.0223 </DOCNO>
