<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indian Scientist Forecasts Major Quake in Assam </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, April 27 (Xinhua) -- An earthquake greater than
eight degree on the Richter Scale is possible in India's eastern
state of Assam at any time before the year 2010, said a renowned
Indian environmental scientist.
</P>
<P>
Studies on the earthquake of the region indicated that strain
is accumulating in some parts of the region, the Hindu daily on
Monday quoted S. K. Sarmah as saying.
</P>
<P>
Sarmah, a professor at the Department of Environment Science in
Gauhati University, Assam State, said three earthquake clusters
had appeared in the region and in one of these, an earthquake
occurred in 1988.
</P>
<P>
There was also "anomalous variation of compressional wave
velocity ratio with time in the region" and the number of small
magnitude earthquakes was increasing while that of larger
magnitude ones decreasing, he added.
</P>
<P>
"These facts can be explained on the basis of dilatancy model
of earthquake occurrence," he asserted, adding that they tended to
indicate the probability of occurrence of a high magnitude
earthquake in the Western part of the North-East at any time in
the next few years.
</P>
<P>
"Any delay in the occurrence of the earthquake will only
increase its magnitude," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
An earthquake of magnitude greater than eight could destroy
houses, buildings and other structures which were not built with
proper design and in standard areas.
</P>
<P>
The region west of 90 degrees longitude in the North-East of
India is regarded as a high-seismic potential region.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
