<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Building Industry Bleak </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's construction industry
is collapsing because of the suspension of housing schemes and
the failure by building societies to release mortgage funds for
home-seekers, The Herald Daily reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Over 72,000 jobs have been lost in the construction industry
over the past two years as the industry begins to feel the harsh
economic conditions in the country.
</P>
<P>
In an interview at the weekend, Chairman of the Zimbabwe
Building Contractors' Association Obert Sibanda said most
contractors depended on building houses and would fold up unless
the situation changed.
</P>
<P>
He said there were over 100,000 workers in the industry in
1996 but by late 1997, the figure had been reduced to less than
28,000 due to retrenchments.
</P>
<P>
"The future of the industry is very bleak. Many contractors
have folded while others are struggling to survive. If the
situation does not change soon more contractors will be forced to
fold," Sibanda said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
