<HEADLINE> Nuclear City Welcomes More Tourists </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XINING, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Qinghai Province in northwest
China is preparing to welcome tourists to the country's first
nuclear research center, known as "nuclear city."
</P>
<P>
The center, which was the site of China's first atom bomb and
hydrogen bomb tests and production, was closed in 1987. It lies in
Haiyan County, 103 kilometers from Xining, the province's capital,
and is the world's first nuclear test ground that has been
retired.
</P>
<P>
Now it has been transformed into a tourism resort after
undergoing strict environmental clearance.
</P>
<P>
This year, the province will set up a museum to display some
firsthand material, objects and models used for nuclear testing.
</P>
<P>
In addition, it will also hold discussions to be attended by
participants in the tests and film a documentary for the show in
an attempt to offer tourists a better understanding of the tests.
</P>
<P>
The planned projects are open to investors from China and
overseas, and some favorable policies will also be offered,
according to Zhao Yanqi, director of the province's Tourism
Bureau.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
