<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila, World Bank Set Talks for Banking Reform Loan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 27 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank is pushing for more
stringent banking reform as part of the conditions for the
granting of a 300-million-U.S.-dollar bank sector adjustment loan
to the Philippine government.
</P>
<P>
A World Bank mission will arrive here on Wednesday for fresh
negotiations with the Central Bank of the Philippines to thresh
out issues blocking the release of the loan, local newspaper
Manila Standard reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper quoted sources privy to the talks said among the
new measures being pushed by the World Bank were amendments to the
Bank Secrecy Law and a reserve requirement on foreign currency
deposits (FCDs).
</P>
<P>
The international financial institution wants to amend the law,
which prevents authorities from prying open bank accounts unless
it's in connection with a court case, to limit the ability of
erring banks to hide questionable transactions.
</P>
<P>
Fearing the amendment to the secrecy law will open the door to
possible abuse by regulators and other government authorities,
Central Bank Governor Singson Gabriel Singson has objected to the
revision of the law, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The planned World Bank loan is expected to further boost the
central bank's international reserves which are vital for a stable
Philippine peso. 
</P>
</TEXT>
