<HEADLINE> Record First Quarter Offshore Oil Output </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 27 (Xinhua) -- China pumped over 4.2 million
tons of offshore crude oil and 900 million cu.m. of gas in the
first three months of this year, up sharply on the figure of the
same 1997 period.
</P>
<P>
"The record quarterly output was achieved with an average daily
crude output topping 49,100 tons," according to a senior official
with the China National Offshore Oil Corp. (CNOOC).
</P>
<P>
The official noted that the oil and gas output will rise even
further during 1998, with a group of new oil-gas fields scheduled
to enter operations in the South China Sea and Bohai Sea before
the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
He noted that CNOOC has entered its prime period of
development, with 19 operational offshore oil-gas fields
maintaining high output levels.
</P>
<P>
Offshore crude oil output for this year is expected to exceed
the 1997 figure of 16 million tons. 
</P>
