<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines Eyes Stricter Anti-dumping Policies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 27 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines' Tariff Commission
has proposed to introduce various changes in trade measures in
view of the expected heavy dumping by other currency
crisis-affected economies, local newspaper the Business Daily said
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Tariff Commissioner Emmanuel Velasco was quoted as saying there
was a need to put in place stricter trade measures that will
protect local firms from being put at a disadvantage.
</P>
<P>
Because of the economic crisis in Asia, Velasco said the
possible heavy influx of cheap imported commodities from countries
with excess capacities like South Korea and Thailand could pose a
big threat to local manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
The proposals raised by the Tariff Commission include the
passage of Export Valuation System, which facilitates the change
in the basis of dutiable value of imported articles from home
consumption value to transaction value.
</P>
<P>
Under the system, the Bureau of Customs can adjust the export
price of an imported commodity to a higher level and use this as
basis in computing for the import duties.
</P>
<P>
Velasco said that there was also a need for industry groups to
prepare domestic price and export price profiles of selected
commodities prior to the regional crisis so that government can
compare it with the current prices. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
