<HEADLINE> China Expands High-Yield Hybrid Rice Coverage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, April 27 (Xinhua) -- China will grow high-yield
hybrid rice on 433,000 hectares in 1998, 160,000 hectares more
than last year, as part of its effort to produce additional grain
to meed the increasing demand of the growing population.
</P>
<P>
The National Hybrid Rice Technological Engineering Research
Center project reports that hybrid rice, which yields an average
10 percent more per unit output than other varieties, has been
introduced to the nation's major rice producing areas.
</P>
<P>
Central China's Hunan Province has dedicated 6,600 hectares for
experimental hybrid rice cultivation. Yuan Longping, well-known as
the "Father of Hybrid Rice," will direct the 200-odd technicians
participating in the project.
</P>
<P>
Hybrid rice developed by Yuan is currently grown on over 200
million hectares throughout the country and has yielded an
additional 300 million tons. Yuan's rice is widely used in over 20
countries. 
</P>
