<DOCNO> XIE19980427.0248 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ancient Plank Road Discovered in Central China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZHENGZHOU, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Chinese archeologists have
unearthered the ruins of a plank road, salt warehouse and ferry
crossing over 1,100 years ago along the Yellow River.
</P>
<P>
Experts say the discoveries will offer a full view of water
transportation in ancient China.
</P>
<P>
The ancient plank road found Xin'an County, central China's
Henan Province, provided east-west for a 4,000 meter stretch on
both sides of a 36-km section of the Yellow River.
</P>
<P>
"Traces of ancient boat trackers and towropes are readily
discernible." according to the archeologists, who have also
concluded that the water level of the Yellow River some 10
meters lower than that some 1,000 years ago.
</P>
<P>
Eighteen-odd inscriptions penned by ancient scholars were found
on rocks alongside the plank road. The inscriptions mainly
recorded the status of water transportation during the Tang
Dynasty (618-907).
</P>
<P>
The discovery of salt warehouses some 12 km west of the
Xiaolongdi Reservoir reveals that the Yellow River was an
important channel for salt transportation in ancient China.
</P>
<P>
Four ferry crossings were discovered in nearby valleys,
including some which are still in use today.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980427.0249 </DOCNO>
