<HEADLINE> China's Property Price Index Recovers in First Quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 27 (Xinhua) -- China's real estate price index
recovered in the first quarter of this year, with the price index
in 16 major cities picking up by varying degrees except in Hong
Kong and Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
According to a report compiled by the China Real Estate Index
System, the price index in Hong Kong and Shanghai in the first
quarter were 6,059 points and 809 points respectively, down 1,338
points and 16 points from the fourth quarter of 1997.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong's real estate price index dropped since October last
year as a result of the impact of the Asian financial crisis. It
is expected to be stable in the coming months because the local
government has taken a series of measures to stabilize the real
estate price.
</P>
<P>
The country's real estate situation took a favorable turn in
the first quarter, along with the clarification of associated
policies and measures, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Real estate investment in the first quarter increased by 9.2
percent compared with the corresponding period last year.
</P>
<P>
The total floor space of commercial housing sold in the first
quarter increased by 41 percent.
</P>
<P>
Beijing's housing market was extremely favorable as a result of
the high purchasing power of work units. The high purchasing power
resulted in a short supply of housing in the city center and a
rise in prices, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The total floor space of Beijing's residential housing sold in
the first quarter increased by 32.4 percent, compared with the
corresponding period last year.
</P>
<P>
In China's southern cities, such as Shenzhen, individuals'
purchasing of houses made up more than 80 percent of the total.
</P>
<P>
The growth rate of real estate investment in Chongqing and
Tianjin rose between 25 percent to 75 percent, while investment in
coastal areas, such as Shanghai, Guangdong and Hainan was zero or
dropped because of an oversupply of real estate.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
