<HEADLINE> Bosnian Serb Refugees Arrive in Banja Luka </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, April 26 (Xinhua) -- Under the escort of the
Multinational Stabilization Force, 150 Serb refugees in the
Bosnian Muslim-Croat Federation Sunday arrived in Banja Luka, the
capital of the Bosnian Serb Republic.
</P>
<P>
They are part of the more than 200 Serb families, that were
sent back home to Drvar, west Bosnia, in the past two years under
the Dayton peace accord after the ending of the
three-and-half-year war in 1995, Yugoslav news agency Tanjug
reported.
</P>
<P>
However, the returning Serbs have been continuously attacked by
the Croat extremists. With their dwellings burned down, many of
them have become refugees once again, said the report.
</P>
<P>
Momcilo Krajisnik, Serb member of the Bosnian Presidency,
released a statement on the same day condemning the Croat
extremists for their persecution against the returning refugees
and expressing his dissatisfaction with the international
community for its failure to guarantee the safety of refugees on
repatriation.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, German Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel stated that the
Bosnian Croat leaders should be held responsible for the
persecution of the refugees.
</P>
<P>
He asked them to pressure the local Croat authorities and
guarantee that no similar things will happen again, the report
said. 
</P>
