<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tibetans Beginning To Celebrate Birthdays (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, April 27 (Xinhua) -- On his birthday earlier this year,
Dandzim was being given white hadas, the ceremonial silk scarfs
used to show respect among Tibetans, by his son and daughter, and
just sat there with his mouth wide open while someone gave him a
piece of cake and the grandchildren began to sing "Happy birthday".
</P>
<P>
The 80-year-old Tibetan, who worked for a serf-owner in
childhood, explained that people like him never celebrated their
birthdays and said, "I'm happy when my children celebrate my
birthday for me."
</P>
<P>
The Tibetans did not traditionally bear their date of birth in
mind and have only started to celebrate their birthdays recently
like people elsewhere. "My father only knows that he was born in
the Year of the Ram," says Dainba Gyalcan, the old man's son, "and
he really doesn't know the exact date of his birth."
</P>
<P>
"He has been a hardworking man all his life, and it is our duty
to show filial piety to him," the son, who is a middle school
teacher, continues and then explains, "We have all agreed that we
celebrate his birthday on the first day of the Tibetan lunar new
year."
</P>
<P>
As more Tibetan women give birth in hospitals and the permanent
residence registration system expands, birthday celebrations have
become increasingly popular among Tibetans and the younger
generation pay more attention to their birthdays, and parents buy
cakes and gifts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
