<HEADLINE> Tibetans Begin to Celebrate Birthdays (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"March 25 is the busiest day for us because we have to
prepare a cake and gifts and have to invite relatives to the
birthday party," said Wangdui, a 35-year-old medical worker, "we
just want my child to know that he is one year older, and all
friends and relatives have hopes for him."
</P>
<P>
As a result of this growth in birthday celebrations, there are
more cake shops in Lhasa, Tibet's capital.
</P>
<P>
Xu Geping, a baker who began his business in 1985, says that
since the 1990s, there has been an increasing number of people,
mostly Tibetans, buying cakes in his shop, and each day, at least
a dozen cakes are ordered.
</P>
<P>
And, he says, "The people of Lhasa are particular about the
taste of the cake," so he recently got more modern equipment from
Shanghai and other materials from overseas to make better cakes.
</P>
<P>
Banjue, of the Tibetan Academy of Social Sciences, says that
the popularity of birthday celebrations among Tibetans shows that
Tibetans are good at absorbing cultural traits from other people,
and, "It also means that the Tibetan people have a more positive
attitude towards life." 
</P>
</TEXT>
