<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading Australian Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, April 27 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading Australian newspapers on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Australian:
</P>
<P>
-- Australian public education chiefs have vowed to halt the
loss of students to private schools by increasing the choice of
schools and subjects.
</P>
<P>
The Sydney Morning Herald:
</P>
<P>
-- The parent company of stevedoring company Patrick came under
pressure Sunday night to pay for restarting operations with its
sacked 1,400 waterfront workers after the Maritime Union of
Australia retreated from an offer of financial help.
</P>
<P>
The Age:
</P>
<P>
-- A meeting of 5000 police officers in Australia's Victoria
state Sunday voted to take widespread industrial action after
rejecting the latest pay offer, and vowed to go on strike if
management retaliated.
</P>
<P>
The Australian Financial Review:
</P>
<P>
-- The Australian coalition government's uncompromising
commitment to its waterfront reform strategy will be tested after
a new poll has revealed a collapse in the government's standing
amid strong voter rejection of the tactics being used. 
</P>
