<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Analysis: Canadian PM to Promote Cuban Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, April 26 (Xinhua) -- Canadian Prime Minister Jean
Chretien left here Sunday for a landmark visit to Cuba, the first
by a Canadian prime minister in 22 years.
</P>
<P>
During the three-day trip, Chretien is expected to discuss with
his Cuban host President Fidel Castro issues such as trade,
investment and human rights.
</P>
<P>
Some bilateral agreements will also be signed to encourage
exchanges of medical personnel, audio-visual products and sports
teams.
</P>
<P>
But the most important thing about the trip is not what
Chretien is doing there, but the fact that he's there at all,
analysts here said.
</P>
<P>
Chretien's visit will demonstrate to the world that Canada
pursues a foreign policy independent of the United States,
according to the analysts.
</P>
<P>
Canada has long maintained a policy of "constructive
engagement" with Cuba, which is in sharp contrast to the U.S.
policy of isolation in the past 36 years.
</P>
<P>
It took the lead in fighting against the 1996 U.S. Helms-Burton
law, which seeks to tighten its embargo on Cuba by penalizing
foreign companies that invest or do business there.
</P>
<P>
"Isolation leads nowhere," Chretien said, days before the visit
that has been rescheduled to last from April 26 to 28 due to
domestic issues.
</P>
<P>
"We believe the best way to promote our values is through
dialogue, not isolation," noted Chretien, who is the first
Canadian prime minister to visit Cuba since his predecessor Pierre
Trudeau made a trip in 1976.
</P>
<P>
Though Chretien's visit caused sharp words from Washington, it
has met welcome from most of the rest of the Western Hemisphere
since it was leaked at last week's summit of Americas in Santiago,
Chile.
</P>
<P>
"There is quited a strong push on in the entire hemisphere for
a different approach to Cuba, including them in the inter-American
system," said a senior Canadian official.
</P>
<P>
The analysts believed that Chretien's visit will also be a plus
in promoting Canadian-Cuban economic and political relations.
</P>
<P>
Despite the U.S. embargo, trade and investment cooperation
between Canada and Cuba has grown quickly in recent years.
</P>
<P>
Canada stands now as Cuba's third largest trading partner, with
two-way trade reaching 712 million dollars (500 million USD) last
year.
</P>
<P>
Canada also has the largest foreign investment projects in Cuba.
The new terminal at Havana's international airport that Chretien
will inaugurate has been built with Canadian financing.
</P>
<P>
Bilateral political dialogues have been active and on the rise.
Last year, the two countries signed a joint declaration, which
identified 14 areas in which the two countries agreed to work
together.
</P>
<P>
Chretien and Castro are expected to review progress in these
areas during their meetings, the Canadian official said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
