<HEADLINE> Britain's Police Chief for Nuclear Safety Resigns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 26 (Xinhua) -- Britain's police chief for nuclear
safety resigned after a disagreement over policing levels at
Dounreay plant, a government spokeswoman said on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The spokeswoman for the Department of Trade and Industry said
Anthony Pointer, chief constable for the United Kingdom Atomic
Energy Authority (UKAEA), stepped down after the government
decided to accept four kg of nuclear waste from Georgia and stored
the material at the Dounreay plant in Scotland.
</P>
<P>
Pointer had privately warned that British nuclear plants,
including Dounreay, were open to attacks by terrorists and
environmental activists because of staff shortages.
</P>
<P>
The police chief complained that the UKAEA police force should
have 470 officers policing the installations but now had fewer
than 400.
</P>
<P>
The spokeswoman said the UKAEA had agreed to meet the cost of
six extra security staff after Pointer was still determined to
leave the office.
</P>
<P>
The nuclear shipment from Georgia arrived on Friday and will be
reprocessed at Dounreay under a deal between the United States,
Britain and Georgia aimed at preventing it from falling into the
hands of rebels opposed to the Georgian government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
